{"segment_id": "00014", "page_num": 14, "segment": "INTRODUCTION\n\nOVERWHELMING\nOBSTACLES\n\nIn 1805, England had a problem. Napoléon had conquered big\nchunks of Europe and planned the invasion of England. But to cross\nthe Channel, he needed to wrest control of the sea away from the\nEnglish. O the southwest coast of Spain, the French and Spanish\ncombined eet of thirty-three ships met the smaller British eet of\ntwenty-seven ships. The well-developed tactics of the day were for\nthe two opposing eets to each stay in line, ring broadsides at each\nother. But British admiral Lord Nelson had a strategic insight. He\nbroke the British eet into two columns and drove them at the\nFranco-Spanish eet, hitting their line perpendicularly. The lead\nBritish ships took a great risk, but Nelson judged that the lesstrained Franco-Spanish gunners would not be able to compensate\nfor the heavy swell that day. At the end of the Battle of Trafalgar,\nthe French and Spanish lost twenty-two ships, two-thirds of their\neet. The British lost none. Nelson was mortally wounded,\nbecoming, in death, Britain’s greatest naval hero. Britain’s naval\ndominance was ensured and remained unsurpassed for a century\nand a half.\n\nNelson’s challenge was that he was outnumbered. His strategy\nwas to risk his lead ships in order to break the coherence of his\nenemy’s eet. With coherence lost, he judged, the more experienced\nEnglish captains would come out on top in the ensuing melee. Good\nstrategy almost always looks this simple and obvious and does not\ntake a thick deck of PowerPoint slides to explain. It does not pop out\nof some “strategic management” tool, matrix, chart, triangle, or llin-the-blanks scheme. Instead, a talented leader identies the one or", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "4", "chapter_title": "WHY SO MUCH BAD STRATEGY?", "l1_summary": "He\nbroke the British eet into two columns and drove them at the\nFranco-Spanish eet, hitting their line perpendicularly. At the end of the Battle of Trafalgar,\nthe French and Spanish lost twenty-two ships, two-thirds of their\neet. The British lost none.", "l2_summary": "In 1805, England had a problem. O the southwest coast of Spain, the French and Spanish\ncombined eet of thirty-three ships met the smaller British eet of\ntwenty-seven ships. But British admiral Lord Nelson had a strategic insight. He\nbroke the British eet into two columns and drove them at the\nFranco-Spanish eet, hitting their line perpendicularly. At the end of the Battle of Trafalgar,\nthe French and Spanish lost twenty-two ships, two-thirds of their\neet. The British lost none.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 13, "segment_id": "00013"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 15, "segment_id": "00015"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["ships", "british", "spanish", "nelson", "lost", "england", "english", "french", "twenty", "each"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Lord Nelson"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Nelson's Strategy", "Battle of Trafalgar"], "key_concepts": ["strategic insight", "coherence loss", "naval dominance"], "problem_statement": "How to overcome an outnumbered fleet in a naval battle", "solution_approach": "Breaking the enemy's line and exploiting their weaknesses", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00015", "page_num": 15, "segment": "two critical issues in the situation---the pivot points that can\nmultiply\nfocuses and\nconcentrates action and resources on them.\n\nthe eectiveness of eort---and\n\nthen\n\nDespite the roar of voices wanting to equate strategy with\nambition, leadership, “vision,” planning, or the economic logic of\ncompetition, strategy is none of these. The core of strategy work is\nalways the same: discovering the critical factors in a situation and\ndesigning a way of coordinating and focusing actions to deal with\nthose factors.\n\nA leader’s most important responsibility is identifying the biggest\nchallenges to forward progress and devising a coherent approach to\novercoming them. In contexts ranging from corporate direction to\nnational security, strategy matters. Yet we have become so\naccustomed to strategy as exhortation that we hardly blink an eye\nwhen a leader spouts slogans and announces high-sounding goals,\ncalling the mixture a “strategy.” Here are four examples of this\nsyndrome.\n\nThe event was a “strategy retreat.” The CEO had modeled it on\na similar event at British Airways he had attended several years\nbefore. About two hundred upper-level managers from around\nthe world gathered in a hotel ballroom where top management\npresented a vision for the future: to be the most respected and\nsuccessful company in their eld. There was a specially\nproduced motion picture featuring the rm’s products and\nservices being used in colorful settings around the world. There\nwas an address by the CEO accompanied by dramatic music to\nhighlight the company’s “strategic” goals: global leadership,\ngrowth, and high shareholder return. There were breakouts into\nsmaller groups to allow discussion and buy-in. There was a\ncolorful release of balloons. There was everything but strategy.\nAs an invited guest, I was disappointed but not surprised.\n\nA specialist in bonds, Lehman Brothers had been a pioneer in\nthe new wave of mortgage-backed securities that buoyed Wall\nStreet in the 2002--6 period. By 2006, signs of strain were", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "4", "chapter_title": "WHY SO MUCH BAD STRATEGY?", "l1_summary": "Despite the roar of voices wanting to equate strategy with\nambition, leadership, “vision,” planning, or the economic logic of\ncompetition, strategy is none of these. There was a\ncolorful release of balloons. There was everything but strategy.", "l2_summary": "Despite the roar of voices wanting to equate strategy with\nambition, leadership, “vision,” planning, or the economic logic of\ncompetition, strategy is none of these. The core of strategy work is\nalways the same: discovering the critical factors in a situation and\ndesigning a way of coordinating and focusing actions to deal with\nthose factors. In contexts ranging from corporate direction to\nnational security, strategy matters. The event was a “strategy retreat.” The CEO had modeled it on\na similar event at British Airways he had attended several years\nbefore. There was a\ncolorful release of balloons. There was everything but strategy.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 14, "segment_id": "00014"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 16, "segment_id": "00016"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["strategy", "there", "critical", "situation", "leadership", "vision", "factors", "leader", "most", "high"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["British Airways", "Lehman Brothers"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_s