{"segment_id": "00020", "page_num": 20, "segment": "process is basically a game of setting performance goals---so much\nmarket share and so much prot, so many students graduating high\nschool, so many visitors to the museum---then there remains a\nyawning gap between these ambitions and action. Strategy is about\nhow an organization will move forward. Doing strategy is guring\nout how to advance the organization’s interests. Of course, a leader\ncan set goals and delegate to others the job of guring out what to\ndo. But that is not strategy. If that is how the organization runs, let’s\nskip the spin and be honest---call it goal setting.\n\nThe purpose of this book is to wake you up to the dramatic\ndierences between good strategy and bad strategy and to give you\na leg up toward crafting good strategies.\n\nA good strategy has an essential logical structure that I call the\nkernel. The kernel of a strategy contains three elements: a diagnosis,\na guiding policy, and coherent action. The guiding policy species\nthe approach to dealing with the obstacles called out in the\ndiagnosis. It is like a signpost, marking the direction forward but not\ndening the details of the trip. Coherent actions are feasible\ncoordinated policies, resource commitments, and actions designed\nto carry out the guiding policy.\n\nOnce you gain a facility with the structure and fundamentals of a\ngood strategy, you will develop the parallel ability to detect the\npresence of bad strategy. Just as you do not need to be a director to\ndetect a bad movie, you do not need economics, nance, or any\nother abstruse special knowledge to distinguish between good and\nbad strategy. For example, looking at the U.S. government’s\n“strategy” for dealing with the 2008 nancial crisis, you will see\nthat essential elements are missing. In particular, there was no\nocial diagnosis of the underlying malady. So, there can be no\nfocus of resources and actions on a cure. There has only been a shift\nof resources from the public to the banks. You do not need a PhD in\nmacroeconomics\nfrom\nthis\nto make\nunderstanding the nature of good strategy itself.\n\njudgment---it\n\nfollows", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "4", "chapter_title": "WHY SO MUCH BAD STRATEGY?", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Strategy is about\nhow an organization will move forward. Doing strategy is guring\nout how to advance the organization’s interests. But that is not strategy.", "l2_summary": "Strategy is about\nhow an organization will move forward. Doing strategy is guring\nout how to advance the organization’s interests. But that is not strategy. The purpose of this book is to wake you up to the dramatic\ndierences between good strategy and bad strategy and to give you\na leg up toward crafting good strategies. A good strategy has an essential logical structure that I call the\nkernel. The kernel of a strategy contains three elements: a diagnosis,\na guiding policy, and coherent action.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 19, "segment_id": "00019"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 21, "segment_id": "00021"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["strategy", "good", "there", "organization", "will", "diagnosis", "guiding", "policy", "actions", "need"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["strategy", "goal setting", "diagnosis"], "key_concepts": ["good strategy", "bad strategy", "kernel of a strategy"], "problem_statement": "The gap between setting performance goals and taking action to achieve them", "solution_approach": "Crafting good strategies with a logical structure including diagnosis, guiding policy, and coherent actions", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00021", "page_num": 21, "segment": "Bad strategy is more than just the absence of good strategy. Bad\nstrategy has a life and logic of its own, a false edice built on\nmistaken foundations. Bad strategy may actively avoid analyzing\nobstacles because a leader believes that negative thoughts get in the\nway. Leaders may create bad strategy by mistakenly treating\nstrategy work as an exercise in goal setting rather than problem\nsolving. Or they may avoid hard choices because they do not wish\nto oend anyone---generating a bad strategy that tries to cover all\nthe bases rather than focus resources and actions.\n\nThe creeping spread of bad strategy aects us all. Heavy with\ngoals and slogans, the national government has become less and less\nable to solve problems. Corporate boards sign o on strategic plans\nthat are little more than wishful thinking. Our education system is\nrich with targets and standards, but poor in comprehending and\ncountering the sources of underperformance. The only remedy is for\nus to demand more from those who lead. More than charisma and\nvision, we must demand good strategy.", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "4", "chapter_title": "WHY SO MUCH BAD STRATEGY?", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Bad strategy is more than just the absence of good strategy. The creeping spread of bad strategy aects us all. More than charisma and\nvision, we must demand good strategy.", "l2_summary": "Bad strategy is more than just the absence of good strategy. Bad\nstrategy has a life and logic of its own, a false edice built on\nmistaken foundations. Bad strategy may actively avoid analyzing\nobstacles because a leader believes that negative thoughts get in the\nway. Leaders may create bad strategy by mistakenly treating\nstrategy work as an exercise in goal setti