{"segment_id": "00040", "page_num": 40, "segment": "aimed their designs at dierent purposes. In either case, such\ncompetitors will have diculty in dealing with Wal-Mart. Copying\nelements of its strategy piecemeal, there will be little benet. A\ncompetitor would have to adopt the whole design, not just a part of\nit.\n\nThere is much more to be discussed: rst-mover advantages,\nquantifying its cost advantage, the issue of competence and learning\ndeveloped over time, the function of leadership, and whether this\ndesign can work in cities. We proceed.\n\nWith fteen minutes to go, I let the discussion wind down. They\nhave done a good job analyzing Wal-Mart’s business, and I say so.\nBut, I tell them, there is one more thing. Something I barely\nunderstand but that seems important. It has to do with the\n“conventional wisdom”---the phrase from the case I put on the\nwhiteboard at the beginning of the class: “A full-line discount store\nneeds a population base of at least 100,000.”\n\nI turn to Bill and say: “You started us out by arguing that Walton\nbroke the conventional wisdom. But the conventional wisdom was\nbased on the straightforward logic of xed and variable cost. It takes\na lot of customers to spread the overhead and keep costs and prices\nlow. Exactly how did Walton break the iron logic of cost?”\n\nI push ahead, putting Bill into a role: “I want you to imagine that\nyou are a Wal-Mart store manager. It’s 1985 and you are unhappy\nwith the whole company. You feel that they don’t understand your\ntown. You complain to your dad, and he says, ‘Why don’t we just\nbuy them out? We can run the store ourselves.’ Assuming Dad has\nthe resources, what do you think of his proposal?”\n\nBill blinks, surprised at being put on the spot for a second time.\nHe thinks a bit, then says, “No, it’s not a good idea. We couldn’t\nmake a go of it alone. The Wal-Mart store needs to be part of the\nnetwork.”\n\nI turn back the whiteboard and stand right next to the boxed\nprinciple: “A full-line discount store needs a population base of at\nleast 100,000.” I repeat his phrase, “The Wal-Mart store needs to be\npart of the network,” while drawing a circle around the word\n“store.” Then I wait.", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "In either case, such\ncompetitors will have diculty in dealing with Wal-Mart. It has to do with the\n“conventional wisdom”---the phrase from the case I put on the\nwhiteboard at the beginning of the class: “A full-line discount store\nneeds a population base of at least 100,000.” The Wal-Mart store...", "l2_summary": "In either case, such\ncompetitors will have diculty in dealing with Wal-Mart. They\nhave done a good job analyzing Wal-Mart’s business, and I say so. It has to do with the\n“conventional wisdom”---the phrase from the case I put on the\nwhiteboard at the beginning of the class: “A full-line discount store\nneeds a population base of at least 100,000.” I turn to Bill and say: “You started us out by arguing that Walton\nbroke the conventional wisdom. I push ahead, putting Bill into a role: “I want you to imagine that\nyou are a Wal-Mart store manager. The Wal-Mart store needs to be part of the\nnetwork.”", "prev_page": {"page_num": 39, "segment_id": "00039"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 41, "segment_id": "00041"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["store", "mart", "needs", "have", "there", "part", "cost", "conventional", "wisdom", "bill"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Wal-Mart"], "people": ["Bill", "Walton"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frame