{"segment_id": "00046", "page_num": 46, "segment": "CHAPTER THREE\n\nBAD\nSTRATEGY\n\nBad strategy is not simply the absence of good strategy. It grows out\nof specic misconceptions and leadership dysfunctions. Once you\ndevelop the ability to detect bad strategy, you will dramatically\nimprove your eectiveness at judging, inuencing, and creating\nstrategy. To detect a bad strategy, look for one or more of its four\nmajor hallmarks:\n\nFlu. Flu is a form of gibberish masquerading as strategic\nconcepts or arguments. It uses “Sunday” words (words that are\ninated and unnecessarily abstruse) and apparently esoteric\nconcepts to create the illusion of high-level thinking.\n\nFailure to face the challenge. Bad strategy fails to recognize or\ndene the challenge. When you cannot dene the challenge,\nyou cannot evaluate a strategy or improve it.\n\nMistaking goals for strategy. Many bad strategies are just\nstatements of desire rather than plans for overcoming obstacles.\n\nBad strategic objectives. A strategic objective is set by a leader\nas a means to an end. Strategic objectives are “bad” when they\nfail to address critical issues or when they are impracticable.\n\nTHE ORIGIN OF THE “BAD STRATEGY” CONCEPT", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Bad strategy is not simply the absence of good strategy. Bad strategic objectives. THE ORIGIN OF THE “BAD STRATEGY” CONCEPT", "l2_summary": "Bad strategy is not simply the absence of good strategy. To detect a bad strategy, look for one or more of its four\nmajor hallmarks: Bad strategy fails to recognize or\ndene the challenge. Mistaking goals for strategy. Bad strategic objectives. THE ORIGIN OF THE “BAD STRATEGY” CONCEPT", "prev_page": {"page_num