{"segment_id": "00094", "page_num": 94, "segment": "CHAPTER FIVE\n\nTHE KERNEL OF GOOD STRATEGY\n\nGood strategy is coherent action backed up by an argument, an\neective mixture of thought and action with a basic underlying\nstructure I call the kernel. A good strategy may consist of more than\nthe kernel, but if the kernel is absent or misshapen, then there is a\nserious problem. Once you apprehend this kernel, it is much easier\nto create, describe, and evaluate a strategy. The kernel is not based\non any one concept of advantage. It does not require one to sort\nthrough legalistic gibberish about the dierences between visions,\nmissions, goals, strategies, objectives, and tactics. It does not split\nstrategies into corporate, business, and product levels. It is very\nstraightforward.\n\nThe kernel of a strategy contains three elements:\n\nA diagnosis that denes or explains the nature of the challenge.\nA good diagnosis simplies the often overwhelming complexity\nof reality by identifying certain aspects of the situation as\ncritical.\n\nA guiding policy for dealing with the challenge. This is an overall\napproach chosen to cope with or overcome the obstacles\nidentied in the diagnosis.\n\nA set of coherent actions that are designed to carry out the\nguiding policy. These are steps that are coordinated with one\nanother to work together in accomplishing the guiding policy.\n\nHere are some examples:", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "THE KERNEL OF GOOD STRATEGY The kernel is not based\non any one concept of advantage. The kernel of a strategy contains three elements:", "l2_summary": "THE KERNEL OF GOOD STRATEGY Good strategy is coherent action backed up by an argument, an\neectiv