{"segment_id": "00101", "page_num": 101, "segment": "company do? The dominant view at the company and among Wall\nStreet analysts was that IBM was too integrated. The new industry\nstructure was fragmented and, it was argued, IBM should be broken\nup and fragmented to match. As Gerstner arrived, preparations were\nunder way for separate stock oerings for various pieces of IBM.\n\nAfter studying the situation, Gerstner changed the diagnosis. He\nbelieved that in an increasingly fragmented industry, IBM was the\none company that had expertise in all areas. Its problem was not\nthat it was integrated but that it was failing to use the integrated\nskills it possessed. IBM, he declared, needed to become more\nintegrated---but this time around customer solutions rather than\nhardware platforms. The primary obstacle was the lack of internal\ncoordination and agility. Given this new diagnosis, the guiding\npolicy became to exploit the fact that IBM was dierent, in fact,\nunique. IBM would oer customers tailored solutions to their\ninformation-processing problems, leveraging its brand name and\nbroad expertise, but willing to use outside hardware and software as\nrequired. Put simply, its primary value-added activity would shift\nfrom systems engineering to IT consulting, from hardware to\nsoftware. Neither the “integration is obsolete” nor the “knowing all\naspects of IT is our unique ability” viewpoints are, by themselves,\nstrategies. But these diagnoses take the leader, and all who follow,\nin very dierent directions.\n\nTHE GUIDING POLICY\n\nThe guiding policy outlines an overall approach for overcoming the\nobstacles highlighted by the diagnosis. It is “guiding” because it\nchannels action in certain directions without dening exactly what\nshall be done. Kennan’s containment and Gerstner’s drawing on all\nof IBM’s resources to solve customers’ problems are examples of\nguiding policies. Like the guardrails on a highway, the guiding\npolicy directs and constrains action without fully dening its\ncontent.", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "The dominant view at the company and among Wall\nStreet analysts was that IBM was too integrated. The new industry\nstructure was fragmented and, it was argued, IBM should be broken\nup and fragmented to match. Given this new diagnosis, the guiding\npolicy became to exploit the fact that IBM was...", "l2_summary": "The dominant view at the company and among Wall\nStreet analysts was that IBM was too integrated. The new industry\nstructure was fragmented and, it was argued, IBM should be broken\nup and fragmented to match. As Gerstner arrived, preparations were\nunder way for separate stock oerings for various pieces of IBM. He\nbelieved that in an increasingly fragmented industry, IBM was the\none company that had expertise in all areas. Its problem was not\nthat it was integrated but that it was failing to use the integrated\nskills it possessed. Given this new diagnosis, the guiding\npolicy became to exploit the fact that IBM was dierent, in fact,\nunique.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 100, "segment_id": "00100"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 102, "segment_id": "00102"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["guiding", "integrated", "policy", "company", "fragmented", "gerstner", "diagnosis", "hardware", "industry", "expertise"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["IBM"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "IBM", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["IBM's strategic shift", "industry fragmentation", "customer-centric solutions"], "key_concepts": ["diagnosis of the problem", "guiding policy", "internal coordination and agility"], "problem_statement": "How IBM should respond to industry fragmentation", "solution_approach": "Shifting from hardware integration to customer-focused IT consulting", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00102", "page_num": 102, "segment": "Good guiding policies are not goals or visions or images of\ndesirable end states. Rather, they dene a method of grappling with\nthe situation and ruling out a vast array of possible actions. For\nexample, Wells Fargo’s corporate vision is this: “We want to satisfy\nall of our customers’ nancial needs, help them succeed nancially,\nbe the premier provider of nancial services in every one of our\nmarkets, and be known as one of America’s great companies.”5\n\nThis “vision” communicates an ambition, but it is not a strategy\nor a guiding policy because there is no information about how this\nambition will be accomplished. Wells Fargo chairman emeritus and\nformer CEO Richard Kovacevich knew this and distinguished\nbetween this vision and his company’s guiding policy of using the\nnetwork eects of cross-selling. That is, Kovacevich believed that\nthe more dierent nancial products Wells Fargo could sell to a\ncustomer, the more the company would know about that customer\nand about its whole network of customers. That information would,\nin turn, help it create and sell more nancial products. This guiding\npolicy, in contrast to Wells Fargo’s vision, calls out a way of\ncompeting---a way of trying to use the company’s large scale to\nadvantage.\n\nYou may correctly observe that many other people use the term\n“strategy” for what I am calling the “guiding policy.” I have found\nthat dening a strategy as just a broad guiding policy is a mistake.\nWithout a diagnosis, one cannot evaluate alternative guiding\npolicies. Without working through to at least the rst round of\naction one cannot be sure that the guiding policy can be\nimplemented. Good strategy is not just “what” you are trying to do.\nIt is also “why” and “how” you are doing it.\n\nA good guiding policy tackles the obstacles identied in the\ndiagnosis by creating or drawing upon sources of advantage. Indeed,\nthe heart of the matter in strategy is usually advantage. Just as a\nlever uses mechanical advantage to multiply force, strategic\nadvantage multiplies the eectiveness of resources and/or actions.\nImportantly, not all advantage is competitive. In nonprot and\npublic policy situations, good strategy creates advantage by\nmagnifying the eects of resources and actions.", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "This “vision” communicates an ambition, but it is not a strategy\nor a guiding policy because there is no information about how this\nambition will be accomplished. This guiding\npolicy, in contrast to Wells Fargo’s vision, calls out a way of\ncompeting---a way of trying to use the company’s large...", "l2_summary": "Good guiding policies are not goals or visions or images of\ndesirable end states. This “vision” communicates an ambition, but it is not a strategy\nor a guiding policy because there is no information about how this\nambition will be accomplished. This guiding\npolicy, in contrast to Wells Fargo’s vision, calls out a way of\ncompeting---a way of trying to use the company’s large scale to\nadvantage. Without a diagnosis, one cannot evaluate alternative guiding\npolicies. Good strategy is not just “what” you are trying to do. A good guiding policy tackles the obstacles identied in the\ndiagnosis by creating or drawing upon sources of advantage.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 101, "segment_id": "00101"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 103, "segment_id": "00103"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["guiding", "policy", "advantage", "strategy", "good", "wells", "fargo", "vision", "nancial", "actions"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Wells Fargo"], "people": ["Richard Kovacevich"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "Wells Fargo", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["guiding policies", "corporate vision", "strategic advantage"], "key_concepts": ["guiding policy", "vision", "network effects", "cross-selling"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00103", "page_num": 103, "segment": "In most modern treatments of competitive strategy, it is now\ncommon to launch immediately into detailed descriptions of specic\nsources of competitive advantage. Having lower costs, a better\nbrand, a faster product-development cycle, more experience, more\ninformation about customers, and so on, can all be sources of\nadvantage. This is all true, but it is important to take a broader\nperspective. A good guiding policy itself can be a source of\nadvantage.\n\nA guiding policy creates advantage by anticipating the actions and\nreactions of others, by reducing the complexity and ambiguity in the\nsituation, by exploiting the leverage inherent in concentrating eort\non a pivotal or decisive aspect of the situation, and by creating\npolicies and actions that are coherent, each building on the other\nrather than canceling one another out. (These sources of advantage\nare discussed in detail in chapter 6, “Using Leverage.”)\n\nFor example, Gerstner’s “provide customer solutions” policy\ncertainly counted on the advantages implicit in IBM’s world-class\ntechnological depth and expertise in almost all areas of data\nprocessing. But the policy itself also created advantage by resolving\nthe uncertainty about what to do, about how to compete, and about\nhow to organize. It also began the process of coordinating and\nconcentrating IBM’s vast resources on a specic set of challenges.\n\nTo look more closely at how a guiding policy works, follow the\nthinking of Stephanie, a friend who owns a corner grocery store. She\ndoes the accounts, manages personnel, sometimes runs the cash\nregister, and makes all the decisions. Several years ago, Stephanie\ntold me about some of the issues she was facing. She was\nconsidering whether she should keep prices down or oer more\nexpensive, fresh organic produce. Should she begin to stock more\nAsian staples for the many Asian students who lived in the area?\nShould the store be open longer hours? How important was it to\nhave a helpful, friendly sta that gets to know the regulars? Would\nadding a second checkout stand pay o? What about parking in the\nalley? Should she advertise in the local college newspaper? Should\nshe paint the ceiling green or white? Should she put some items on\nsale each week? Which ones?", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "A good guiding policy itself can be a source of\nadvantage. (These sources of advantage\nare discussed in detail in chapter 6, “Using Leverage.”) But the policy itself also created advantage by resolving\nthe uncertainty about what to do, about how to compete, and about\nhow to organize.", "l2_summary": "Having lower costs, a better\nbrand, a faster product-development cycle, more experience, more\ninformation about customers, and so on, can all be sources of\nadvantage. This is all true, but it is important to take a broader\nperspective. A good guiding policy itself can be a source of\nadvantage. (These sources of advantage\nare discussed in detail in chapter 6, “Using Leverage.”) But the policy itself also created advantage by resolving\nthe uncertainty about what to do, about how to compete, and about\nhow to organize. Should the store be open longer hours?", "prev_page": {"page_num": 102, "segment_id": "00102"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 104, "segment_id": "00104"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["advantage", "should", "more", "policy", "sources", "guiding", "competitive", "specic", "important", "itself"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["IBM"], "people": ["Gerstner", "Stephanie"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "IBM", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["competitive strategy", "guiding policy", "resource concentration"], "key_concepts": ["sources of competitive advantage", "anticipating actions and reactions", "creating coherent policies"], "problem_statement": "How to create a guiding policy that provides competitive advantage", "solution_approach": "Anticipate others' actions, reduce complexity, exploit leverage, and create coherent policies", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00104", "page_num": 104, "segment": "An economist would tell her that she should take actions that\nmaximize prot, a technically correct but useless piece of advice. In\nthe economics textbook it is simple: choose the rate of output Q that\nprovides the biggest gap between revenue and cost. In the real\nworld, however, “maximize prot” is not a helpful prescription,\nbecause the challenge of making, or maximizing, prot is an illstructured problem. Even in a corner grocery store, there are\nhundreds or thousands of possible adjustments one can make, and\nmillions in a business of any size---the complexity of the situation\ncan be overwhelming.\n\nThinking about her store, Stephanie diagnosed her challenge to be\ncompetition with the local supermarket. She needed to draw\ncustomers away from a store that was open 24/7 and had lower\nprices. Seeking a way forward, she believed that most of her\ncustomers were people who walked by the store almost every day.\nThey worked or lived nearby. Scanning her list of questions and\nalternatives, she determined that there was a choice between\nserving the more price-conscious students or the more time-sensitive\nprofessionals. Transcending thousands of individual choices and\ninstead framing the problem in terms of choosing among a few\ncustomer groups provided a dramatic reduction in complexity.\n\nOf course, if both of these customer segments could be served\nwith the same policies and actions, then the dichotomy would have\nbeen useless and should be cast aside. In Stephanie’s case, the\ndierence seemed signicant. More of her customers were students,\nbut the professionals who stopped in made much larger purchases.\nPushing further along, Stephanie began to explore the guiding\npolicy of “serve the busy professional.” After some more tinkering,\nStephanie sharpened the guiding policy a bit more, deciding to\ntarget “the busy professional who has little time to cook.”\n\nThere was no way to establish that this particular guiding policy\nwas the only good one, or the best one. But, absent a good guiding\npolicy, there is no principle of action to follow. Without a guiding\npolicy, Stephanie’s actions and resource allocations would probably\nbe inconsistent and incoherent, ghting with one another and\ncanceling one another out. Importantly, adopting this guiding policy", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "There was no way to establish that this particular guiding policy\nwas the only good one, or the best one. But, absent a good guiding\npolicy, there is no principle of action to follow. Importantly, adopting this guiding policy", "l2_summary": "Thinking about her store, Stephanie diagnosed her challenge to be\ncompetition with the local supermarket. She needed to draw\ncustomers away from a store that was open 24/7 and had lower\nprices. There was no way to establish that this particular guiding policy\nwas the only good one, or the best one. But, absent a good guiding\npolicy, there is no principle of action to follow. Without a guiding\npolicy, Stephanie’s actions and resource allocations would probably\nbe inconsistent and incoherent, ghting with one another and\ncanceling one another out. Importantly, adopting this guiding policy", "prev_page": {"page_num": 103, "segment_id": "00103"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 105, "segment_id": "00105"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["guiding", "policy", "stephanie", "more", "store", "there", "would", "actions", "prot", "customers"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Stephanie"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["customer segmentation", "guiding policy", "complexity reduction"], "key_concepts": ["illstructured problem", "maximize profit", "customer groups"], "problem_statement": "How to compete with a supermarket in terms of customer attraction and retention.", "solution_approach": "Identifying key customer segments and formulating a guiding policy.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00105", "page_num": 105, "segment": "helped reveal and organize the interactions among the many\npossible actions. Considering the needs of the busy professional with\nlittle time to cook, she could see that the second checkout stand\nwould help handle the burst of trac at 5 p.m. So would more\nparking in the alley. In addition, she felt she could take space\ncurrently used for selling munchies to students and oer prepared\nhigh-quality take-home foods instead. Professionals, unlike students,\nwould not come shopping at midnight, so there was no need for\nvery late hours. The busy professionals would appreciate adequate\nstang after work and, perhaps, at lunchtime. Having a guiding\npolicy helped create actions\nthat were coordinated and\nconcentrated, focusing her eorts.\n\nCOHERENT ACTION\n\nMany people call the guiding policy “the strategy” and stop there.\nThis is a mistake. Strategy is about action, about doing something.\nThe kernel of a strategy must contain action. It does not need to\npoint to all the actions that will be taken as events unfold, but there\nmust be enough clarity about action to bring concepts down to\nearth. To have punch, actions should coordinate and build upon one\nanother, focusing organizational energy.\n\nMoving to Action\n\nINSEAD, a global business school located in France, was the\nbrainchild of Harvard professor General Georges F. Doriot. The\nINSEAD library holds a bronze statue of Doriot inscribed with his\nobservation “Without action, the world would still be an idea.”\n\nIn many situations, the main impediment to action is the forlorn\nhope that certain painful choices or actions can be avoided---that\nthe whole long list of hoped-for “priorities” can all be achieved. It is\nthe hard craft of strategy to decide which priority shall take\nprecedence. Only then can action be taken. And, interestingly, there", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Strategy is about action, about doing something. The kernel of a strategy must contain action. Only then can action be taken.", "l2_summary": "helped reveal and organize the interactions among the many\npossible actions. So would more\nparking in the alley. Many people call the guiding policy “the strategy” and stop there. Strategy is about action, about doing something. The kernel of a strategy must contain action. Only then can action be taken.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 104, "segment_id": "00104"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 106, "segment_id": "00106"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["action", "actions", "would", "there", "strategy", "many", "take", "helped", "busy", "could"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["she"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["statue"], "topics": ["strategy", "action planning", "store management"], "key_concepts": ["guiding policy", "coherent action", "prioritization"], "problem_statement": "Improving store operations for busy professionals", "solution_approach": "Analyzing customer needs, reallocating space, and implementing a focused strategy", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00106", "page_num": 106, "segment": "is no greater tool for sharpening strategic ideas than the necessity to\nact.\n\nThe president of the European Business Group had a discrete\nprivate oce in a classic London town home, just west of St. James’\nPark. I was there to discuss progress on the company’s “PanEuropean” initiative.\n\nA consumer goods producer, the company had a typically complex\ninternational organization. There were country-based marketing\norganizations; globally run manufacturing operations; and four\nproduct development centers, one in North America, one in Japan,\none in Germany, and one in the United Kingdom. Product managers\nwere responsible for coordinating activities but had no direct\nauthority. Products tended to be tailored to country or regional\ndierences, partly as a result of some local acquisitions and partly\ndue to perceptions of local dierences in tastes.\n\nSenior management believed that the company’s European\nbusiness was too fragmented. They wanted most of the products\noered in Europe to be Pan-European, exploiting greater economies\nof scale in both production and marketing. Management had spent\ntime and eort communicating the message about a Pan-European\nproduct line and had created some mechanisms to bring it about.\nThe heads of the country-based organizations were placed on a PanEurope Executive Committee, which met once a quarter. Developers\nfrom Germany and the United Kingdom were rotated between the\ntwo locations. A New Products group had been created to consult\nwith all departments on opportunities for Pan-European concepts\nand brands. Part of each executive’s evaluation for promotion was\nbased on his or her contribution to the Pan-European initiative.\nDespite these measures, nothing much had happened. The German\nand British developers each claimed that their initiatives were\nunsupported by the other. The one British-German joint initiative\nhad not been picked up by the rest of the organization.", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "A consumer goods producer, the company had a typically complex\ninternational organization. Management had spent\ntime and eort communicating the message about a Pan-European\nproduct line and had created some mechanisms to bring it about. The one British-German joint initiative\nhad not been picked up...", "l2_summary": "The president of the European Business Group had a discrete\nprivate oce in a classic London town home, just west of St. A consumer goods producer, the company had a typically complex\ninternational organization. Product managers\nwere responsible for coordinating activities but had no direct\nauthority. Senior management believed that the company’s European\nbusiness was too fragmented. Management had spent\ntime and eort communicating the message about a Pan-European\nproduct line and had created some mechanisms to bring it about. The one British-German joint initiative\nhad not been picked up by the rest of the organization.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 105, "segment_id": "00105"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 107, "segment_id": "00107"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["european", "company", "initiative", "country", "based", "product", "products", "greater", "business", "group"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["consumer goods producer"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "consumer goods producer", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Pan-European initiative", "product development centers", "organizational structure"], "key_concepts": ["fragmented business operations", "Pan-European product line", "cross-border collaboration challenges"], "problem_statement": "The company's European business was too fragmented, with products tailored to local differences and little cross-border collaboration.", "solution_approach": "Management aimed to create a Pan-European product line by establishing a Pan-European Executive Committee, rotating developers between locations, and creating a New Products group. However, these measures did not lead to significant progress due to lack of support from country-based organizations.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00107", "page_num": 107, "segment": "As we discussed the situation, my client’s frustration was evident.\nI stopped taking notes, and we both got up and walked over to the\nwindow, looking down on the mews houses below. “Suppose,” I\nsaid, “that this was really important, really top-priority critical.\nSuppose you absolutely had to get some Pan-European products\ndeveloped and marketed in the next eighteen months or everything\nwould collapse. What would you do then?”\n\n“For one thing,” he said, throwing his arms up in mock surrender,\n“I would close one of the development groups. They spend more\ntime bickering than developing.”\n\nThen he thought for a moment and said, “I just might close both\nand start over in the Netherlands. There is a market-test oce there\nwe could use as a seed. We could take some of the best people from\nthe UK and Germany and start fresh. Still, that doesn’t solve the\nproblem of getting the country managers on board.”\n\n“And the country managers’ lack of enthusiasm is because ...?” I\n\nasked.\n\n“Well, each country manager has spent years understanding the\nspecial conditions in a country, tailoring products and marketing\nprograms to that country’s local conditions. They don’t trust the\nPan-European idea. The French don’t want to waste marketing\neorts on products they see as ‘too British’ or ‘too German.’ And\nthere really has not yet been a compelling Pan-European product\nthat all could get behind. If it were already a success in three or four\ncountries, the rest would get behind it. But everyone has their\ncurrent portfolio of products to worry about.”\n\n“Right,” I said. “Their jobs are running the present country-based\nsystem. And you want new Pan-European initiatives. Now, you can\nuse a shoe to hammer a nail, but it will take a long time. Don’t you\nneed a dierent tool for this task? If it were really important to get\nthis done, I think you know how you would do it.”\n\n“Of course,” he said. “We could have a single group develop, roll\nout, and market Pan-European products and take full prot\nresponsibility.”\n\n“At the same time,” I added, “you would have to intervene in the\ncountry-based system with special budget overrides for this", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "“Suppose,” I\nsaid, “that this was really important, really top-priority critical. What would you do then?” They don’t trust the\nPan-European idea.", "l2_summary": "“Suppose,” I\nsaid, “that this was really important, really top-priority critical. What would you do then?” “And the country managers’ lack of enthusiasm is because ...?” I They don’t trust the\nPan-European idea. And you want new Pan-European initiatives. “Of course,” he said.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 106, "segment_id": "00106"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 108, "segment_id": "00108"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["country", "would", "said", "european", "products", "really", "could", "time", "there", "take"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["my client"], "products": ["Pan-European products"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Product Development", "Cross-Country Collaboration", "Management Strategies"], "key_concepts": ["Pan-European product development", "Country manager resistance", "Reorganization for effi