{"segment_id": "00110", "page_num": 110, "segment": "distinctive than a “sporty Volvo.” These two sets of concepts and\nactions were in conict rather than being coherent.\n\nWhat about a list of nonconicting but uncoordinated actions? In\n2003, I worked with a company whose initial “strategy” was to (1)\nclose a plant in Akron and open a new plant in Mexico, (2) spend\nmore on advertising, and (3) initiate a 360-degree feedback\nprogram. Now these actions may all have been good ideas, but they\ndid not complement one another. They are “strategic” only in the\nsense that each probably requires the approval of top management.\nMy view is that doing these things might be sound operational\nmanagement, but it did not constitute a strategy. A strategy\ncoordinates action to address a specic challenge. It is not dened\nby the pay grade of the person authorizing the action.\n\nThe idea that coordination, by itself, can be a source of advantage\nis a very deep principle. It is often underappreciated because people\ntend to think of coordination in terms of continuing mutual\nadjustments among agents. Strategic coordination, or coherence, is\nnot ad hoc mutual adjustment. It is coherence imposed on a system\nby policy and design. More specically, design is the engineering of\nt among parts, specifying how actions and resources will be\ncombined. (This approach to coherence is the subject of chapter 9,\n“Using Design.”)\n\nAnother powerful way to coordinate actions is by the specication\nof a proximate objective. By “proximate,” I mean a state of aairs\nclose enough at hand to be feasible. If an objective is clear and\nfeasible, it can help coordinate both problem solving and direct\naction. (You will nd more about this important tool in chapter 7,\n“Proximate Objectives.”)\n\nStrategy is visible as coordinated action imposed on a system.\nWhen I say strategy is “imposed,” I mean just that. It is an exercise\nin centralized power, used to overcome the natural workings of a\nsystem. This coordination is unnatural in the sense that it would not\noccur without the hand of strategy.\n\nThe idea of centralized direction may set o warning bells in a\nmodern educated person. Why does it make sense to exercise\ncentralized power when we know that many decisions are eciently", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "A strategy\ncoordinates action to address a specic challenge. It is coherence imposed on a system\nby policy and design. Strategy is visible as coordinated action imposed on a system.", "l2_summary": "What about a list of nonconicting but uncoordinated actions? A strategy\ncoordinates action to address a specic challenge. Strategic coordination, or coherence, is\nnot ad hoc mutual adjustment. It is coherence imposed on a system\nby policy and design. Strategy is visible as coordinated action imposed on a system. When I say strategy is “imposed,” I mean just that.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 109, "segment_id": "00109"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 111, "segment_id": "00111"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["strategy", "actions", "action", "coordination", "more", "sense", "coherence", "imposed", "system", "design"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], 