{"segment_id": "00151", "page_num": 151, "segment": "I rst discovered the discipline of design in my rst job out of\ncollege, working as a systems engineer at the Jet Propulsion\nLaboratories. It was a dream job, doing conceptual designs of a\nmission to Jupiter, a project that would later be named Voyager.\n\nJPL was organized around the subsystems of a spacecraft---\ncommunications, power, structures, attitude control, computing and\nsequencing, and so on.* I was in the systems division, where the job\nof a systems engineer was the overall architecture of the spacecraft\nand working out the coordination among the specications of all the\ndierent subsystems.\n\nOur basic constraint was weight. We expected that the Titan IIIC\nrocket would launch about 1,200 pounds into a trajectory toward\nJupiter. If we could use the larger Saturn 1B, then we could plan on\na 3,000-pound spacecraft. Over a year, I sketched out two designs.\nEach was a dierent conguration based on a dierent weight\nbudget.\n\nWith 3,000 pounds to work with, the design work was relatively\neasy. We could essentially bolt together fairly well-understood\nsubsystems. Consequently, the divisions would not have to\ncoordinate very much because the design challenge was relatively\nlow. But if we had only 1,200 pounds to work with, things were\nmore dicult. Interactions began to play a big role.\n\nMost of the work in systems design is guring out the\ninteractions, or trade-os, as they were called. The moment you\ntried to optimize any one part, that choice immediately posed\nproblems for other parts. The weight constraint made the whole\nthing a web of competing needs, and it all had to be considered\ntogether. Cutting the weight of the radioactive thermal power unit\nmeant less power for the radio, limiting it to about 35 watts. To\ncompensate for the low-powered radio, we could try for a more\nfocused dish antenna and seek greater accuracy in pointing the dish\nat Earth. That meant better sensors, more complex control logic, and\nmore fuel for attitude control were required. Try to cut the shielding\non the spacecraft by putting the radioactive power source on a", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Our basic constraint was weight. With 3,000 pounds to work with, the design work was relatively\neasy. Most of the work in systems design is guring out the\ninteractions, or trade-os, as they were called.", "l2_summary": "I rst discovered the discipline of design in my rst job out of\ncollege, working as a systems engineer at the Jet Propulsion\nLaboratories. Our basic constraint was weight. If we could use the larger Saturn 1B, then we could plan on\na 3,000-pound spacecraft. With 3,000 pounds to work with, the design work was relatively\neasy. But if we had only 1,200 pounds to work with, things were\nmore dicult. Most of the work in systems design is guring out the\ninteractions, or trade-os, as they were called.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 150, "segment_id": "00150"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 152, "segment_id": "00152"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["design", "systems", "spacecraft", "power", "weight", "could", "work", "more", "would", "subsystems"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Jet Propulsion Laboratories"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["Titan IIIC rocket", "Saturn 1B", "radioactive thermal power unit", "dish antenna"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_i