mbedded deeply within the human fabric of the enterprise, and\nmost rms nd this a dicult maneuver. Xerox, for example, built a\nworld-class fast-response repair and maintenance service to take\ncare of its installed base of copying machines. Thus, its initial\nresource---the patent on plain-paper copying---was used to create a", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "be available, for a time, without further labor. Thus, a strong resource position can obviate the need for\nsophisticated design-type strategy. Yes, there was\ninventive genius in the creation of these strategic resources, but\nprots from those resources can be sustained, for a time, without\ngenius.", "l2_summary": "be available, for a time, without further labor. And, like a dam,\nonce that well-protected resource position was achieved, it persisted\nfor many years. Thus, a strong resource position can obviate the need for\nsophisticated design-type strategy. Yes, there was\ninventive genius in the creation of these strategic resources, but\nprots from those resources can be sustained, for a time, without\ngenius. Existing resources can be the lever for the creation of new\nresources, but they can also be an impediment to innovation. Thus, its initial\nresource---the patent on plain-paper copying---was used to create a", "prev_page": {"page_num": 154, "segment_id": "00154"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 156, "segment_id": "00156"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["resource", "resources", "time", "position", "years", "without", "xerox", "plain", "paper", "copying"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "com