{"segment_id": "00162", "page_num": 162, "segment": "CHAPTER TEN\n\nFOCUS\n\nIt is a bright April morning and my upcoming session is for\nexecutive MBAs. Some are already there, Web browsing, reading\nnewspapers, or studying. Today’s case is on Crown Cork & Seal, a\nmaker of metal containers.1 It is one of the oldest cases in the\nstrategy collection. Updated many times, the case today takes the\ncompany through 1989.\n\nMy objectives are not to show my class how to manage a can\ncompany, or even how to create a good strategy. Instead, they are\n(1) to teach them how to identify a company’s strategy, (2) to\ndeepen their skills at analyzing qualitative information, and (3) to\nexplore a particular mixture of policy and positioning called focus.\n\nCrown’s strategy had been crafted in the early 1960s by John F.\nConnelly, whose tight-sted direction of Crown had become\nvirtually a folktale in American business. It had been, for example, a\nfavorite of legendary stock picker Peter Lynch, manager of Fidelity’s\nMagellan Fund. Over thirty-ve years, the company had achieved a\nphenomenal record, providing an average return to shareholders of\n19 percent per year---an especially impressive performance given\nthe intense competition in its industry.\n\nWhat was Crown’s secret? The case repeats the conventional\nwisdom that Crown specialized in containers for hard-to-hold\nproducts such as aerosols and carbonated soft drinks. While true, of\ncourse, this description is neither complete nor terribly useful in\nunderstanding how Crown competed. Nevertheless, most analysts\nstop there, gladly accepting this description of Crown’s strategy.\nThey will not have noticed that the details of Crown’s policies point\nin other directions as well. In general, people will not push further", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Today’s case is on Crown Cork & Seal, a\nmaker of metal containers.1 It is one of the oldest cases in the\nstrategy collection. Crown’s strategy had been crafted in the early 1960s by John F. What was Crown’s secret?", "l2_summary": "Today’s case is on Crown Cork & Seal, a\nmaker of metal containers.1 It is one of the oldest cases in the\nstrategy collection. Updated many times, the case today takes the\ncompany through 1989. My objectives are not to show my class how to manage a can\ncompany, or even how to create a good strategy. Crown’s strategy had been crafted in the early 1960s by John F. What was Crown’s secret? Nevertheless, most analysts\nstop there, gladly accepting this description of Crown’s strategy.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 161, "segment_id": "00161"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 163, "segment_id": "00163"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["crown", "strategy", "company", "case", "focus", "there", "today", "containers", "description", "will"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Crown Cork & Seal"], "people": ["John F. Connelly", "Peter Lynch"], "products": ["aerosols", "carbonated soft drinks"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "Crown Cork & Seal", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["company strategy", "focus strategy", "executive MBA case study"], "key_concepts": ["strategy identification", "qualitative information analysis", "focus strategy"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_