{"segment_id": "00188", "page_num": 188, "segment": "to build large-scale nut-processing facilities. The economies of scale\nin processing have so far prevented smaller competitors from\nachieving equivalent costs.\n\nIt must have taken iron nerve to wait years for the strategy to\n\nwork. “You are still looking ve to ten years ahead?” I query.\n\n“It is one of the big benets of being a private company. When I\nrst bought these lands from major oil companies, they were\nlooking ahead one quarter or one year. They wanted to get the\nassets ‘o their books’ to make their nancial ratios look better. We\ncan do more with these businesses because we don’t suer the crazy\npressures that are put on a public company.”\n\nSome Advantages Are More “Interesting” Than Others\n\nWhen another person speaks you hear both less and more than they\nmean. Less because none of us can express the full extent of our\nunderstanding, and more because what another says is constantly\nmixing and interacting with your own knowledge and puzzlements.\nWhen Stewart Resnick explained what made a business “interesting”\nto him, I made an unexpected connection to aspects of the concept\nof competitive advantage that I had been puzzling over for some\ntime. I felt something click into place in my mind. To explain, I have\nto go back to 2002 when my UCLA colleague Steven Lippman and I\ncreated a thought experiment about competitive advantage.\n\nOur\n\nthought experiment* concerned an\n\nimaginary “silver\nmachine” left behind by a passing UFO. It could produce $10\nmillion per year in raw silver at no cost---it used no inputs of\nenergy, materials, or labor. There were no taxes and the constant\ninterest rate was 10 percent. The original nder of the silver\nmachine sold it to a new owner for $100 million. Did this new\nowner, we asked, have a competitive advantage in the silver\nbusiness?\n\nThe silver machine problem became an underground puzzle in the\nstrategy eld. The silver machine was obviously a low-cost producer\n---zero cost is about as low as it goes. The conundrum was that this", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "The original nder of the silver\nmachine sold it to a new owner for $100 million. Did this new\nowner, we asked, have a competitive advantage in the silver\nbusiness? The silver machine was obviously a low-cost producer\n---zero cost is about as low as it goes.", "l2_summary": "Some Advantages Are More “Interesting” Than Others When another person speaks you hear both less and more than they\nmean. imaginary “silver\nmachine” left behind by a passing UFO. The original nder of the silver\nmachine sold it to a new owner for $100 million. Did this new\nowner, we asked, have a competitive advantage in the silver\nbusiness? The silver machine was obviously a low-cost producer\n---zero cost is about as low as it goes.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 187, "segment_id": "00187"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 189, "segment_id": "00189"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["silver", "have", "when", "more", "machine", "because", "competitive", "advantage", "cost", "scale"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["major oil companies"], "people": ["Stewart Resnick", "Steven Lippman"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["large-scale processing facilities", "competitive advantage", "private company strategy"], "key_concepts": ["economies of scale", "competitive advantage", "private company flexibility"], "problem_statement": "How to achieve competitive advantage in a highly regulated and capital-intensive industry.", "solution_approach": "Long-term strategic planning and leveraging the benefits of being a private company.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00189", "page_num": 189, "segment": "advantage did not make the new owner any wealthier. Yes, the\nmachine paid out $10 million per year, but that was just an\nordinary 10 percent return on what had been paid to buy it. Its\ncompetitive advantage seemed to have evaporated because of the\nchange in ownership. Yet the machine continued to produce silver\nat zero cost.3\n\nIt took some time, but I can unravel the puzzle. The silver\nmachine does have a competitive advantage in the silver business.4\nThe conundrum disappears when you carefully distinguish between\ncompetitive advantage and nancial gain---many have assumed that\nthey are the same thing, but they are not. But it was Stewart Resnick\nwho helped me see another even more important fact about the\nsilver machine---that its advantage, though real, wasn’t interesting.\n\nThe silver machine’s advantage gives it value, but the advantage\nisn’t interesting because there is no way for an owner to engineer an\nincrease in its value. The machine cannot be made more ecient.\nPure silver cannot be dierentiated. One small producer cannot\npump up the global demand for silver. You can no more increase the\nvalue of the silver machine than you can, by yourself, engineer an\nincrease in the value of a Treasury bond. Therefore, owning this\nadvantage is no more interesting than owning a bond.\n\nFor Stewart Resnick, and now for me, a competitive advantage is\ninteresting when one has insights into ways to increase its value.\nThat means there must be things you can do, on your own, to\nincrease its value.\n\nTo see an example of a major competitive advantage that is,\npresently, not increasing in value, look at eBay. It should be obvious\nthat eBay has a considerable competitive advantage in the global\nperson-to-person auction business. eBay invented this business and\nremains by far the worldwide dominant rm in it. More specically,\neBay’s competitive advantage lies in its unrivaled ability to oer the\nleast expensive, most eective solution to just about anyone who\nwishes to buy or sell a personal item online. Its broad user base,\neasy-to-use software, the PayPal payment system, and its methods of\nrating sellers all give it a considerable advantage over any\ncompeting platform. Over the years, eBay has been very protable.", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Its\ncompetitive advantage seemed to have evaporated because of the\nchange in ownership. The silver\nmachine does have a competitive advantage in the silver business.4\nThe conundrum disappears when you carefully distinguish between\ncompetitive advantage and nancial gain---many have assumed that\nthey...", "l2_summary": "Its\ncompetitive advantage seemed to have evaporated because of the\nchange in ownership. Yet the machine continued to produce silver\nat zero cost.3 The silver\nmachine does have a competitive advantage in the silver business.4\nThe conundrum disappears when you carefully distinguish between\ncompetitive advantage and nancial gain---many have assumed that\nthey are the same thing, but they are not. The silver machine’s advantage gives it value, but the advantage\nisn’t interesting because there is no way for an owner to engineer an\nincrease in its value. You can no more increase the\nvalue of the silver machine than you can, by yourself, engineer an\nincrease in the value of a Treasury bond. Therefore, owning this\nadvantage is no more interesting than owning a bond.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 188, "segment_id": "00188"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 190, "segment_id": "00190"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_