{"segment_id": "00191", "page_num": 191, "segment": "broadening the extent of advantages,\n\ncreating higher demand for advantaged products or services, or\n\nstrengthening the isolating mechanisms that block easy\nreplication and imitation by competitors.\n\nDeepening Advantage\n\nStart by dening advantage in terms of surplus---the gap between\nbuyer value and cost. Deepening an advantage means widening this\ngap by either increasing value to buyers, reducing costs, or both.*\n\nIt would be foolish to attempt to summarize the vast variety of\nmethods and approaches that can be used to make improvements in\ncost and/or value. It is more useful to highlight the two main\nreasons this process stalls.\n\nFirst, management may mistakenly believe that improvement is a\n“natural” process or that it can be accomplished by pressure or\nincentives alone. As Frank Gilbreth pointed out in 1909, bricklayers\nhad been laying bricks for thousands of years with essentially no\nimprovement in tools and technique.5 By carefully studying the\nprocess, Gilbreth was able to more than double productivity without\nincreasing anyone’s workload. By moving the supply pallets of\nbricks and mortar to chest height, hundreds or thousands of\nseparate lifting movements per day by each bricklayer were\navoided. By using a movable scaold, skilled masons did not have to\nwaste time carrying bricks up ladders. By making sure that mortar\nwas the right consistency, masons could set and level a brick with a\nsimple press of the hand instead of the time-honored multiple taps\nwith a trowel. Gilbreth’s lesson, still fresh today, is that incentives\nalone are not enough. One must reexamine each aspect of product\nand process, casting aside the comfortable assumption that everyone\nknows what they are doing. Today, this approach to information\nows and business processes is sometimes called “reengineering” or\nis called, the\n“business-process transformation.” Whatever\n\nit", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Start by dening advantage in terms of surplus---the gap between\nbuyer value and cost. Deepening an advantage means widening this\ngap by either increasing value to buyers, reducing costs, or both.* It is more useful to highlight the two main\nreasons this process stalls.", "l2_summary": "Start by dening advantage in terms of surplus---the gap between\nbuyer value and cost. Deepening an advantage means widening this\ngap by either increasing value to buyers, reducing costs, or both.* It is more useful to highlight the two main\nreasons this process stalls. First, management may mistakenly believe that improvement is a\n“natural” process or that it can be accomplished by pressure or\nincentives alone. As Frank Gilbreth pointed out in 1909, bricklayers\nhad been laying bricks for thousands of years with essentially no\nimprovement in tools and technique.5 By carefully studying the\nprocess, Gilbreth was able to more than double productivity without\nincreasing anyone’s workload. Gilbreth’s lesson, still fresh today, is that incentives\nalone are not enough.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 190, "segment_id": "00190"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 192, "segment_id": "00192"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["process", "advantage", "value", "gilbreth", "bricks", "deepening", "cost", "increasing", "more", "improvement"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Frank Gilbreth"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Advantage Deepening", "Process Improvement", "Management Techniques"], "key_concepts": ["advantage deepening", "surplus", "buyer value", "cost reduction", "reengineering"], "problem_statement": "Stalling process of improvement in cost and value", "solution_approach": "Reexamining each aspect of product and process, moving away from the assumption that everyone knows what they are doing", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00192", "page_num": 192, "segment": "underlying principle is that improvements come from reexamining\nthe details of how work is done, not just from cost controls or\nincentives.\n\nThe same issues that arise in improving work processes also arise\nin the improvement of products, except that observing buyers is\nmore dicult than examining one’s own systems. Companies that\nexcel at product development and improvement carefully study the\nattitudes, decisions, and feelings of buyers. They develop a special\nempathy for customers and anticipate problems before they occur.\n\nThe second reason rms may fail to engage in a process of\nimprovement occurs when\nisolating mechanisms surrounding\nimportant methods are weak. Companies in such situations sensibly\nhope to catch a free ride on the improvements of others. To benet\nfrom investments in improvement, the improvements must either be\nprotected or embedded in a business that is suciently special that\nits methods are of little use to rivals.\n\nBroadening the Extent of Advantage\n\nExtending an existing competitive advantage brings it into new elds\nand new competitions. For example, cell phone banking is a\ngrowing phenomenon outside of the United States, especially in the\nless developed countries. eBay holds substantial skills in payment\nsystems embedded in its PayPal business. If eBay could build on\nthese to create a competitive advantage in cell phone payment\nsystems, it would be extending a competitive advantage.\n\nExtending a competitive advantage requires looking away from\nproducts, buyers, and competitors and looking instead at the special\nskills and resources that underlie a competitive advantage. In other\nwords, “Build on your strengths.”\n\nThe idea that some corporate resources can be put to good use in\nother products or markets is possibly the most basic in corporate\nstrategy.6 Its truth is undeniable yet it is also the source of great\nmischief. Bemused by the idea that their company’s competitive\nstrength lies in vaporous generalities such as “transportation,”", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Broadening the Extent of Advantage Extending an existing competitive advantage brings it into new elds\nand new competitions. If eBay could build on\nthese to create a competitive advantage in cell phone payment\nsystems, it would be extending a competitive advantage.", "l2_summary": "The same issues that arise in improving work processes also arise\nin the improvement of products, except that observing buyers is\nmore dicult than examining one’s own systems. Broadening the Extent of Advantage Extending an existing competitive advantage brings it into new elds\nand new competitions. eBay holds substantial skills in payment\nsystems embedded in its PayPal business. If eBay could build on\nthese to create a competitive advantage in cell phone payment\nsystems, it would be extending a competitive advantage. Extending a competitive advantage requires looking away from\nproducts, buyers, and competitors and looking instead at the special\nskills and resources that underlie a competitive advantage.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 191, "segment_id": "00191"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 193, "segment_id": "00193"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["advantage", "competitive", "improvement", "improvements", "products", "buyers", "systems", "special", "extending", "work"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["eBay"], "people": [], "products": ["cell phone banking", "PayPal"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "