{"segment_id": "00250", "page_num": 250, "segment": "Nvidia’s domain of 3-D graphics has nothing to do with wearing\nspecial glasses or with images that jump o the page or out of the\nmovie screen. The “3-D” in 3-D graphics describes the process used\nto create an image appearing on a computer monitor. If you are\nlooking at a still image, it may not be obvious that is was created\nwith 3-D graphics technology---it is just a still imagedots of color. However, once you gain real-time control over the\nposition of the imaginary camera, the dierence is dramatic. Using a\nmouse or joystick to control the imaginary camera, you can explore\na 3-D scene, viewing it from dierent positions, moving your\nviewpoint around objects to view them from behind or above, and\nmoving into rooms and spaces at will. This is possible because the\ncomputer “knows” the three-dimensional structure of the whole\nscene.\n\nMany of the fundamental components of modern 3-D graphics\ntechnology were developed at the University of Utah as part of a\nstream of research initiated by Professors Ivan Sutherland and David\nEvans in the late 1960s. While other computer science programs\nwere teaching high theory, the Utah program was focused on the\npractical challenge of rendering 3-D images and building ight\nsimulators. The program produced an astounding number of\ncomputer graphics superstars, including John Warnock, founder of\nAdobe Systems; Nolan Bushnell, founder of Atari; Edwin Catmull,\ncofounder of Pixar; and Jim Clark, founder of both Silicon Graphics\nand Netscape.\n\nJim Clark was at Stanford when he formed Silicon Graphics Inc.\n(SGI) in 1982. From its inception, SGI aimed to make the fastest\nhigh-resolution graphics workstations on the planet. SGI’s inuence\non the graphics industry was immense. It not only provided the\nhighest performing graphics hardware, it also developed a special\ngraphics language (GL) that became the standard for many in the\nindustry. Together, SGI’s hardware and GL framed the problem of 3D graphics in a way that became the dominant logic in 3-D graphics.\nCalled the graphics pipeline, this approach rested on breaking the\nimages in the scene into triangles, processing each triangle\nseparately, and putting them back together again to form the nal", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "The “3-D” in 3-D graphics describes the process used\nto create an image appearing on a computer monitor. SGI’s inuence\non the graphics industry was immense. Together, SGI’s hardware and GL framed the problem of 3D graphics in a way that became the dominant logic in 3-D graphics.", "l2_summary": "Nvidia’s domain of 3-D graphics has nothing to do with wearing\nspecial glasses or with images that jump o the page or out of the\nmovie screen. The “3-D” in 3-D graphics describes the process used\nto create an image appearing on a computer monitor. If you are\nlooking at a still image, it may not be obvious that is was created\nwith 3-D graphics technology---it is just a still imagedots of color. Jim Clark was at Stanford when he formed Silicon Graphics Inc. SGI’s inuence\non the graphics industry was immense. Together, SGI’s hardware and GL framed the problem of 3D graphics in a way that became the dominant logic in 3-D graphics.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 249, "segment_id": "00249"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 251, "segment_id": "00251"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["graphics", "computer", "images", "scene", "founder", "special", "image", "still", "technology", "control"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "program