{"segment_id": "00251", "page_num": 251, "segment": "image. One famous use of this technology was rendering the\nvelociraptors in Jurassic Park. In 1992, SGI nally realized the\nwhole graphics pipeline in hardware---a system of banks of\nprocessors tied to a “triangle bus.” Called the Reality Engine, the\nmachine stood four feet high and was priced at over $100,000.\n\nGAMERS\n\nBy the early 1990s it was evident that chips would eventually get\nfast enough to do good 3-D graphics on a PC. But would people use\nthis capability? And, if they did, what would they use it for? Experts\nopined that, perhaps, people would take virtual trips to far-o cities\nvia 3-D graphics, or that real estate agents would use 3-D graphics\nto give prospective buyers virtual walk-throughs of homes. But, as it\nturned out, the market was driven by a dierent application. The\nsudden rise of violent 3-D action games for the PC pulled 3-D chips\nonto the market.\n\nOnce, visiting a friend’s home, I noticed his teenage son, Paul,\nplaying a game called Myst on a personal computer. Paul’s monitor\nshowed a still picture of a scene. Paul clicked on the image of a\nbridge and the CD-ROM drive ground for a few seconds before the\nimage changed to a view from the bridge. Music played, but nothing\nmoved and each new scene took several seconds to render. It was\nthe summer of 1994 and Myst was then a very popular game on\npersonal computers.\n\nTwo weeks later, I visited again, and this time Paul was playing a\ngame called Doom. The image on the screen showed a monster\ndropping into a room on a descending platform. The monster was\nring red blobs at Paul, which streaked across the room. Paul was\nusing the mouse and keyboard to bob and weave away from the red\nblobs. There was no delay. With each ick of his wrist, the image\nshifted as he scrambled around this three-dimensional space. He ran\nthrough a door and down a corridor. The monster followed. Paul\nducked into an alcove, popping out into the corridor to let o a\npistol shot and then back into the alcove to avoid return re. He", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "But would people use\nthis capability? And, if they did, what would they use it for? Paul’s monitor\nshowed a still picture of a scene.", "l2_summary": "By the early 1990s it was evident that chips would eventually get\nfast enough to do good 3-D graphics on a PC. But would people use\nthis capability? And, if they did, what would they use it for? Paul’s monitor\nshowed a still picture of a scene. Paul clicked on the image of a\nbridge and the CD-ROM drive ground for a few seconds before the\nimage changed to a view from the bridge. The monster was\nring red blobs at Paul, which streaked across the room.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 250, "segment_id": "00250"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 252, "segment_id": "00252"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["paul", "image", "would", "graphics", "called", "game", "monster", "chips", "people", "virtual"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "programming", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["SGI"], "people": [], "products": ["Reality Engine", "Myst", "Doom"], "technologies": ["graphics pipeline", "3-D graphics", "CD-ROM drive"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["Reality Engine", "CD-ROM drive"], "topics": ["3-D graphics technology history", "video game industry evolution", "technologi