{"segment_id": "00254", "page_num": 254, "segment": "STRATEGY AT NVIDIA\n\nNvidia was formed in 1993, by Jen-Hsun (pronounced Jen-Sun)\nHuang, Curtis Priem, and Chris Malachowsky. Huang had been an\nengineer-manager at LSI Logic. Priem and Malachowsky had been\nfor hardware\nchief\nengineering, respectively, at Sun Microsystems.\n\ntechnology ocer and vice president\n\nAt that time the industry was alive with talk about the coming\nmultimedia revolution. However, at that moment existing audio\ncards worked with some software and not others. There was no\nstandard way to compress or display video. CD-ROM drives were\nnot fully standardized and there was no standard at all for 3-D\ngraphics. Microsoft’s Windows 95 and the wide use of Internet\nbrowsers were several years in the future.\n\nNvidia executive vice president of sales Je Fisher recalled that\n“the original dream was to be the Sound Blaster of multimedia.” The\ncompany’s rst product, the NV1, introduced in 1995, was intended\nto establish a new multimedia standard. But its considerable audio\ncapabilities were no better than the fast-moving competition’s, and\nits quirky 3-D graphics approach did not catch on. The NV1 was a\ncommercial op.\n\nFaced with the failure of the company’s rst product and the\nsudden rise of 3dfx, Jen-Hsun Huang reformulated the company’s\nstrategy. Key inputs came from a temporary technical advisory\nboard made up of both insiders and expert outsiders.2\n\nThe new strategy was a sharp change in direction. Instead of\nmultimedia, the company would focus on 3-D graphics for desktop\nPCs. Instead of its initial proprietary approach to graphics, the\ncompany would embrace the SGI-based triangle method. About the\nonly thing that stayed unchanged was Nvidia’s commitment to being\na “fabless” chip company, focusing on design and outsourcing\nfabrication.\n\nProgress in the semiconductor industry was based on reducing the\nsize of a transistor. Smaller transistors meant more transistors per\nchip. Plus, smaller transistors were faster and consumed less power.\nThe whole semiconductor industry coordinated around achieving a", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Nvidia was formed in 1993, by Jen-Hsun (pronounced Jen-Sun)\nHuang, Curtis Priem, and Chris Malachowsky. Faced with the failure of the company’s rst product and the\nsudden rise of 3dfx, Jen-Hsun Huang reformulated the company’s\nstrategy. Instead of\nmultimedia, the company would focus on 3-D graphics...", "l2_summary": "Nvidia was formed in 1993, by Jen-Hsun (pronounced Jen-Sun)\nHuang, Curtis Priem, and Chris Malachowsky. At that time the industry was alive with talk about the coming\nmultimedia revolution. CD-ROM drives were\nnot fully standardized and there was no standard at all for 3-D\ngraphics. Nvidia executive vice president of sales Je Fisher recalled that\n“the original dream was to be the Sound Blaster of multimedia.” The\ncompany’s rst product, the NV1, introduced in 1995, was intended\nto establish a new multimedia standard. Faced with the failure of the company’s rst product and the\nsudden rise of 3dfx, Jen-Hsun Huang reformulated the company’s\nstrategy. Instead of\nmultimedia, the company would focus on 3-D graphics for desktop\nPCs.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 253, "segment_id": "00253"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 255, "segment_id": "00255"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["company", "nvidia", "multimedia", "graphics", "strategy", "huang", "industry", "standard", "transistors", "hsun"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "programming|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Nvidia", "LSI Logic", "Sun Microsystems"], "people": ["Jen-Hsun Huang", "Curtis Priem", "Chris Malachowsky", "Je Fisher"], "products": ["NV1"], "technologies": ["3-D graphics", "multimedia", "audio cards", "CD-ROM drives", "Windows 95", "Internet browsers"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "Nvidia", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["company strategy", "product development", "market challenges"], "key_concepts": ["multimedia standard", "3-D graphics focus", "fabless chip company"], "problem_statement": "The initial multimedia product failed, and the company had to reformulate its strategy.", "solution_approach": "Reformulating the strategy to focus on 3-D graphics for desktop PCs and adopting a fabless approach.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00255", "page_num": 255, "segment": "higher level of integration, based on smaller transistors, about every\neighteen months. This rate of progress was called Moore’s law. No\none could jump much ahead of this pace because all the\ntechnologies, from photolithography to optical design to metal\ndeposition to testing, had to advance in lockstep. The industry\ncalled this pattern of collective advance the “road map.”\n\nNvidia’s top management and its technology board sketched out a\ndierent road map, one that would push 3-D graphics performance\nat a much faster rate than Moore’s law predicted. There were two\nfactors crucial to making this happen. First, they anticipated a large\njump in performance from putting more and more of the graphics\npipeline onto a single chip. Second, most manufacturers, such as\nIntel, didn’t keep cramming the maximum number of transistors\npossible onto a chip---they took advantage of increases in density to\nmake more chips per wafer, thereby cutting the cost of a chip.\nNvidia, by contrast, planned to use that extra density to add more\nparallel processors, boosting performance---a consequence of using\nthe Utah-SGI “triangle bus” idea.\n\nOn the demand side, management judged that the market would\nbuy virtually all the graphics processing power that could be\nprovided. There was no sharp call for word processors or\nspreadsheets that ran one hundred times faster, but there was a very\nsharp demand for faster and more realistic graphics. Chief scientist\nDavid Kirk put it this way: “There is a virtually limitless demand for\ncomputational power in 3-D graphics. Given the architecture of the\nPC, there is only so much you can do with a more powerful CPU.\nBut it is easy to use up one teraop of graphics computing power.\nThe GPU [graphics processing unit] is going to be the center of\ntechnology and value added in consumer computing.”\n\nWith regard to a graphics language, Nvidia’s management judged\nthat it would be self-defeating to work with 3dfx’s Glide. Therefore,\nthey bet that Microsoft’s new but unproven DirectX would become a\nworkable high-performance graphics standard. They made this\nassessment after meeting with the DirectX team and nding them to\nbe graphics enthusiasts who wanted to push the frontier as fast as\npossible.", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "First, they anticipated a large\njump in performance from putting more and more of the graphics\npipeline onto a single chip. Chief scientist\nDavid Kirk put it this way: “There is a virtually limitless demand for\ncomputational power in 3-D graphics. But it is easy to use up one teraop of graphics...", "l2_summary": "Nvidia’s top management and its technology board sketched out a\ndierent road map, one that would push 3-D graphics performance\nat a much faster rate than Moore’s law predicted. First, they anticipated a large\njump in performance from putting more and more of the graphics\npipeline onto a single chip. On the demand side, management judged that the market would\nbuy virtually all the graphics processing power that could be\nprovided. Chief scientist\nDavid Kirk put it this way: “There is a virtually limitless demand for\ncomputational power in 3-D graphics. But it is easy to use up one teraop of graphics computing power. With regard to a graphics language, Nvidia’s management judged\nthat it would be self-defeating to work with 3dfx’s Glide.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 254, "segment_id": "00254"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 256, "segment_id": "00256"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["graphics", "more", "there", "would", "performance", "much", "nvidia", "management", "faster", "chip"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "programming", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Nvidia", "Intel", "3dfx", "Utah-SGI", "Microsoft"], "people": ["David Kirk"], "products": [], "technologies": ["Moore’s law", "transistors", "photolithography", "optical design", "metal deposition", "testing", "chip", "wafer", "GPU", "3-D graphics", "triangle bus", "DirectX"], "frameworks": ["null"], "methodologies": ["null"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "Nvidia", "tools_mentioned": ["null"], "topics": ["Nvidia's road map for 3-D graphics performance", "Moore’s law and its impact on technology advancement", "Competitive strategies in the graphics processing industry"], "key_concepts": ["road map", "Moore’s law", "transistor size reduction", "graphics pipeline integration", "chip density utilization", "DirectX standard adoption"], "problem_statement": "How Nvidia developed a faster road map for 3-D graphics performance compared to Moore's law and the industry standards.", "solution_approach": "Nvidia anticipated significant performance gains from integrating more of the graphics pipeline onto a single chip, utilized higher chip density to add parallel processors, and bet on Microsoft’s DirectX as the future standard.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00256", "page_num": 256, "segment": "Finally, CEO Jen-Hsun Huang believed that Nvidia could\nconstruct an advantage by breaking out of the industry’s eighteenmonth cycle. He reasoned that since it looked possible to advance\ngraphics power three times faster than CPU power, Nvidia could\ndeliver a substantial upgrade in graphics power every six months\ninstead of every eighteen months.\n\nThis is the point where a bad strategist would have wrapped the\nconcept of a faster development cycle in slogans about speed,\npower, and growth, and then sought to cash in by taking the\ncompany public. Instead, the Nvidia team designed a set of cohesive\npolicies and actions to turn their guiding policy into reality.\n\nThe rst step\n\nin executing the guiding policy was the\nestablishment of three separate development teams. Each would\nwork to an eighteen-month start-to-market cycle. With overlapping\nschedules, the three teams would deliver a new product every six\nmonths.\n\nA two-month delay in a six-month cycle was much more serious\nthan the same delay in an eighteen-month cycle. Accordingly, the\nsecond set of policies were meant to substantially reduce the delays\nand uncertainty in the development process.\n\nA serious source of possible delays was a design error. After\ndesigning a chip, the company passed the design to a fabricator.\nAfter about one month, engineers received back the rst samples of\nactual chips. If bugs were found in these chips, the design would\nhave to be changed, new masks would have to be created, and a\nnew fabrication run initiated. To address this source of possible\ndelays, Nvidia invested heavily in simulation and emulation\ntechniques and organized its chip design process around these\nmethods.\n\nSuch tools were the forte of founder Chris Malachowsky, and he\npushed the use of these tools for the formal verication of a chip’s\nlogic. Still, even if the logical design was correct, problems might\narise in the physical func