proach to such a problem in established\nindustries would be to have certain board makers work directly with\nNvidia’s emulators early in the development cycle. This, however,", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "In the\nmonths and years to come, Nvidia increasingly relied on contract\nelectronics manufacturers for board production and distribution. The contract manufacturers were free to brand the board as they\nchose; most chose to emphasize the Nvidia name. Over the next ve years, Nvidia continued its...", "l2_summary": "Dell reacted positively and agreed to oer boards with\nNvidia chips, manufactured by Celestica Hong Kong Ltd. In the\nmonths and years to come, Nvidia increasingly relied on contract\nelectronics manufacturers for board production and distribution. The contract manufacturers were free to brand the board as they\nchose; most chose to emphasize the Nvidia name. Over the next ve years, Nvidia continued its pattern of rapid\nreleases, pushing the envelope in 3-D graphics capabilities. On\nthe other hand, as Nvidia’s leaders envisioned, the performance of\ngraphics chips is experienced directly and immediately by users. In this case, the relationship between the chip maker and\nthe board maker altered.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 258, "segment_id": "00258"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 260, "segment_id": "00260"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["nvidia", "board", "performance", "contract", "manufacturers", "graphics", "dell", "industry", "chips", "years"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "programming", "complexity": "int