{"segment_id": "00266", "page_num": 266, "segment": "CHAPTER SIXTEEN\n\nTHE SCIENCE OF STRATEGY\n\nGood strategy is built on functional knowledge about what works,\nwhat doesn’t, and why. Generally available functional knowledge is\nessential, but because it is available to all, it can rarely be decisive.\nThe most precious functional knowledge is proprietary, available\nonly to your organization.\n\nAn organization creates pools of proprietary functional knowledge\nby actively exploring its chosen arena in a process called scientic\nempiricism. Good strategy rests on a hard-won base of such\nknowledge, and any new strategy presents the opportunity to\ngenerate it. A new strategy is, in the language of science, a\nhypothesis, and its implementation is an experiment. As results\nappear, good leaders learn more about what does and doesn’t work\nand adjust their strategies accordingly.\n\nSTRATEGY IS A HYPOTHESIS\n\nStanding in the hangar-sized Hughes Electronics fabrication facility,\nI marvel at the huge communications satellite. It gleams and\nsparkles like a jewel, each part fashioned with exquisite precision. A\nmodern cathedral, the eighteen-thousand-pound device embodies\nthe highest skills and knowledge of my civilization. In it, the\nthree-axis\ntechnologies of orbital mechanics,\norientation, and sophisticated computation, as well as the reception,\namplication, and beaming of electromagnetic waves over entire\ncontinents, are woven together into a working harmony that will\n\nsolar power,", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "THE SCIENCE OF STRATEGY Good strategy is built on functional knowledge about what works,\nwhat doesn’t, and why. STRATEGY IS A HYPOTHESIS", "l2_summary":