plexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Starbucks", "Il Giornale"], "people": ["Schultz"], "products": ["coee", "espresso"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "Starbucks", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Starbucks' business model", "Schultz's vision for coee shops in the US"], "key_concepts": ["radical change in consumer tastes and habits", "proprietary insight", "testing hypothesis with a small investment"], "problem_statement": "How Schultz faced challenges in changing American coee culture to align with Italian espresso bar experiences.", "solution_approach": "Opening a single, authentic Italian-style espresso bar as a test case.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00279", "page_num": 279, "segment": "waiters wore formal shirts and bow ties, and the menu was\npeppered with Italian.\n\nHad Schultz stuck to this initial concept, Il Giornale would have\nremained a single small espresso bar. But, like a good scientist who\ncarefully studies the results of experiments, Schultz and his team\nwere alert to customer response. Il Giornale, once started, became a\nliving experiment.\n\nOne of the most important resources a business can have is\nvaluable privileged information---that is, knowing something that\nothers do not. There is nothing arcane or illicit about such\ninformation---it is generated every day in every operating business.\nAll alert businesspeople can know more about their own customers,\ntheir own products, and their own production technology than\nanyone else in the world. Thus, once Schultz initiated business\noperations, he began to accumulate privileged information.\n\nAs knowledge accumulated, he altered policies. He took the\nItalian o the menu, then eliminated the opera music. He knew the\nbaristas were central, but he did away with their vests and bow ties.\nHe departed from the Milanese model and put in chairs for the sitdown trade. Over more time, Schultz discovered that Americans\nwanted takeout coee so he introduced paper cups. Americans\nwanted nonfat milk in their lattes, so, after a great deal of soul\nsearching, he allowed nonfat milk. In the technical jargon of\ninternational business, he gradually “localized” the Italian espresso\nbar to American tastes.\n\nIn 1987, his company bought out Starbucks’ retail operations and\nadopted the Starbucks name. The new rm combined the old\nStarbucks business of selling dark-roasted arabica coee beans with\nthe new one of operating espresso bars. By 1990, the company was\nprotable. In 1992, it went public with 125 stores and two thousand\nemployees.\n\nBy 2001, Starbucks had become an American icon, with 4,700\nworldwide outlets and $2.6 billion in revenue. The bulk of its\nrevenues came from selling coee drinks---the company called them\nhandcrafted beverages. The rest came from the sale of coee beans,\nsome other food items in its coee bars, and licensing agreements", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "Thus, once Schultz initiated business\noperations, he began to accumulate privileged information. In 1987, his company bought out Starbucks’ retail operations and\nadopted the Starbucks name. The new rm combined the old\nStarbucks business of selling dark-roasted arabica coee beans with\nthe new one of...", "l2_summary": "Had Schultz stuck to this initial concept, Il Giornale would have\nremained a single small espresso bar. There is nothing arcane or illicit about such\ninformation---it is generated every day in every operating business. Thus, once Schultz initiated business\noperations, he began to accumulate privileged information. Over more time, Schultz discovered that Americans\nwanted takeout coee so he introduced paper cups. In 1987, his company bought out Starbucks’ retail operations and\nadopted the Starbucks name. The new rm combined the old\nStarbucks business of selling dark-roasted arabica coee beans with\nthe new one of operating espresso bars.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 278, "segment_id": "00278"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 280, "segment_id": "00280"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["business", "coee", "schultz", "starbucks", "italian", "espresso", "information", "company", "ties", "menu"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Starbucks", "I