{"segment_id": "00283", "page_num": 283, "segment": "CHAPTER SEVENTEEN\n\nUSING\nYOUR HEAD\n\nI am twenty-ve and nervous. Each doctoral student at the Harvard\nBusiness School is expected to write cases based on eld interviews.\nSo, in the summer of 1967, I am in Los Angeles, assigned to write a\nstrategy case. Sitting across from a senior manager’s desk, I hold a\nyellow legal pad and a ballpoint pen, but I have no idea how to\nproceed. No one has coached me on interviewing senior executives\nabout strategy.\n\nFred Fletcher, the general manager of Fansteel Inc.’s Advanced\nStructures division, shows no sign that he has noticed my youth or\ninexperience. He simply asks me how we should begin. I have to say\nsomething, so I say, “Let’s start with what you are trying to\naccomplish here. What is the purpose of the Advanced Structures\ndivision?”\n\nFletcher tells me that the division is charged with integrating the\nactivities of six recently acquired rms, each a specialist in making\nthings out of a high-tech material (for example, titanium,\ncolumbium,\ntungsten, ber-epoxy composites, and specialty\nceramics). The idea is to bring more of a science base to these\nessentially craft-based enterprises and act like a general contractor\nwith respect to aerospace prime contractors.\n\nI am surprised that these high-tech businesses are small\nentrepreneurial job shops. Fletcher explains that they have grown\nup in the Los Angeles area in support of the aerospace industry.\nUniversities don’t teach about real fabrication issues, and neither do\ntrade schools. The large established rms have skills in design but\nlittle knowledge about actually forming objects out of exotic", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "So, in the summer of 1967, I am in Los Angeles, assigned to write a\nstrategy case. What is the purpose of the Advanced Structures\ndivision?” Fletcher explains that they have grown\nup in the Los Angeles area in support of the aerospace industry.", "l2_summary": "So, in the summer of 1967, I am in Los Angeles, assigned to write a\nstrategy case. Sitting across from a senior manager’s desk, I hold a\nyellow legal pad and a ballpoint pen, but I have no idea how to\nproceed. Fred Fletcher, the general manager of Fansteel Inc.’s Advanced\nStructures division, shows no sign that he has noticed my youth or\ninexperience. I have to say\nsomething, so I say, “Let’s start with what you are trying to\naccomplish here. What is the purpose of the Advanced Structures\ndivision?” Fletcher explains that they have grown\nup in the Los Angeles area in support of the aerospace industry.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 282, "segment_id": "00282"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 284, "segment_id": "00284"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["have", "fletcher", "division", "each", "write", "based", "angeles", "strategy", "senior", "manager"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Fansteel Inc.", "Advanced Structures division"], "people": ["Fred Fletcher", "I (author)"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "Fansteel Inc.", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["strategy case writing", "interviewing senior executives", "company integration"], "key_concepts": ["writing strategy cases", "conducting interviews with senior managers", "integrating acquired b