{"segment_id": "00287", "page_num": 287, "segment": "erecting barriers to imitation. Yet, there is a more fundamental\nchallenge common to all contexts. That is the challenge of working\naround one’s own cognitive limitations and biases---one’s own\nmyopia. Our own myopia is the obstacle common to all strategic\nsituations.\n\nBeing strategic is being less myopic---less shortsighted---than\nothers. You must perceive and take into account what others do not,\nbe they colleagues or rivals. Being less myopic is not the same as\npretending you can see the future. You must work with the facts on\nthe ground, not the vague outlines of the distant future. Whether it\nis insight into industry structures and trends, anticipating the\nactions and reactions of competitors, insight into your own\ncompetencies and resources, or stretching your own thinking to\ncover more of the bases and resist your own biases, being “strategic”\nlargely means being less myopic than your undeliberative self.\n\nTIVO\n\nAt eight a.m. the group of seventeen managers settles into the room.\nIt is a rainy fall day in 2005, the second day of a three-day program.\nI am working with the group each morning on strategy. The most\nsenior executive is sitting in the center of the front row, a good sign.\nWhen the senior person sits in the back, and to the side, I have\nlearned that it generally signals an early exit rather than\nengagement.\n\nToday, we are studying TiVo, a much more complicated situation\nthan yesterday’s case. I start the session by joking that I saw some\nlate-night partying and am worried that no one has prepared the\nmaterials. I ask, “Did everyone do the assignment?”\n\nThey all nod armatively or say, “Yes.”\nThe assignment was to write one paragraph describing a\nrecommended strategy for TiVo. The responses are now stacked\nneatly on the podium in the front of the room. I point to the stack\nand say, “Well, then you must have all seen the quick and easy\nsolution to TiVo’s problems!”", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "That is the challenge of working\naround one’s own cognitive limitations and biases---one’s own\nmyopia. Our own myopia is the obstacle common to all strategic\nsituations. Being strategic is being less myopic---less shortsighted---than\nothers.", "l2_summary": "Yet, there is a more fundamental\nchallenge common to all contexts. That is the challenge of working\naround one’s own cognitive limitations and biases---one’s own\nmyopia. Our own myopia is the obstacle common to all strategic\nsituations. Being strategic is being less myopic---less shortsighted---than\nothers. Being less myopic is not the same as\npretending you can see the future. It is a rainy fall day in 2005, the second day of a three-day program.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 286, "segment_id": "00286"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 288, "segment_id": "00288"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["less", "than", "tivo", "more", "strategic", "myopic", "must", "challenge", "common", "working"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["TIVO"], "people": [], "products": ["TiVo"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "TIVO", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["strategic thinking", "myopia in strategy", "TiVo case study"], "key_concepts": ["cognitive limitations and biases", "being less myopic", "perception of industry structures and trends"], "problem_statement": "challenges in strategic thinking and working around cognitive limitations", "solution_approach": "improving perception and reducing bias", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00288", "page_num": 288, "segment": "They laugh because they all appreciate that the situation facing\nTiVo is thorny. There are issues of technology, competition,\nstandards,\nintellectual\nbargaining with cable and satellite TV providers, privacy, and the\nrole of television in marketing.\n\nproperty, manufacturing\n\neciency,\n\nBut\n\nI have glanced briey at their recommendations, having planned\nto compare these pre-discussion commitments to their postdiscussion views, a way of measuring the contribution of the\none-paragraph\ndiscussion.\nrecommendations, I was struck anew by the variety of judgment\nwithin even a homogeneous group like this one. Yesterday, this\ngroup had proven to be unusually open and frank, less selfprotective than most. I decided to work with them on thinking and\njudgment.\n\nlooking\n\nthese\n\nshort\n\nat\n\n“Before we get into TiVo’s situation,” I say, “I want to back up a\nstep and ask you a question that was not on the assignment for\ntoday. I want to ask you how you arrived at your recommendations.\nHow did you come up with your response to this assignment?”\n\nIt isn’t the question they have been expecting, and there is a long\nmoment of quiet. People shift in their seats and look at one another.\nI glance pointedly at the most senior executive. He speaks up, saying\nthat he had “read the case and made some marginal notes.”\n\n“While you were reading the case,” I ask, “what did you think\n\nabout?”\n\n“He was thinking about getting a beer!” a colleague jokes.\nWe all laugh. “Besides the need for a Sam Adams,” I press, “what\n\ndid you think about?”\n\n“Well, it’s actually hard to remember. I guess I was mainly\nthinking that this is a great product, a real innovation, yet the\ncompany is losing money because of the cost of manufacturing the\nboxes.”\n\n“Fine. You began to focus on manufacturing.”\n“Yes, I think they need to stop subsidizing the manufacture of\n\nthese units. I think---”\n\n“Good,” I say. “Let’s not get into the specics of your\nrecommendation just yet. I want to stay with how you arrived at", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "I want to ask you how you arrived at your recommendations. “While you were reading the case,” I ask, “what did you think did you think about?”", "l2_summary": "property, manufacturing I want to ask you how you arrived at your recommendations. How did you come up with your response to this assignment?” “While you were reading the case,” I ask, “what did you think did you think about?” I want to stay with how you arrived at", "prev_page": {"page_num": 287, "segment_id": "00287"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 289, "segment_id": "00289"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["think", "manufacturing", "recommendations", "thinking", "want", "laugh", "because", "situation", "tivo", "there"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["TiVo"], "people": [], "products": ["TiVo"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "TiVo", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["TiVo's business challenges", "group discussion and decision-making"], "key_concepts": ["company situation analysis", "group dynamics", "product innovation"], "problem_statement": "TiVo's financial struggles due to manufacturing costs", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00289", "page_num": 289, "segment": "that insight.”\n\nHe looks down at his copy of the case. It has some notes in the\nright-side margins. I want to see if we can actually talk about where\nhis ideas came from. I called his advice an “insight” to suggest that\nhe need not make up some grandiose story about his analytical\nprowess.\n\n“It’s really just experience, or at least, my experience. I saw these\nlarge losses. And they seem to be due to manufacturing.... Well, no.\nTo be honest, the rst thing I thought of was that most customers\nare paying for a giant hard disk that they don’t need. If you only\nwant to time-shift two programs, you don’t need to store a whole\nseason. So, I thought, why not use smaller disks and make only the\nmore intensive users pay for hardware upgrades?”\n\n“So, your initial idea was ... an intuition ... about an action.\n\nUnbundle the disk capacity, maybe price discriminate?”\n\n“Yeah. That’s it.”\n“Fantastic. Very interesting. Did you go down any other\n\navenues?”\n\n“No.... Hey, you only wanted one paragraph!”\nI am pleased with his contribution. Honest and interesting. Of\ncourse, just because I had asked for only one recommendation didn’t\nmean he was constrained to consider only one approach. But I don’t\nwant to point that out just yet.\n\nI turn to another member of the group who has a hand halfway\nup. She says, “I just thought about the situation and came up with a\nrecommendation. It just sort of emerged as I was thinking about the\nproblem. I realized that if other rms come to dominate the cable\nTV segment, while TiVo holds the satellite TV segment, it will lose\nthe battle for scale.”\n\n“Where did that idea come from?” I ask.\n“Well, I don’t really remember.”\n“That’s how good ideas come to us,” I say. “There are lots of\nsausage-making tools being hawked for strategy work, but good\nideas don’t come out of mechanical tools. Conceptual tools may help\nus get oriented, but, in the end, good ideas basically just pop into\nour heads. It’s called ‘insight.’ ”", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "“It’s really just experience, or at least, my experience. But I don’t\nwant to point that out just yet. She says, “I just thought about the situation and came up with a\nrecommendation.", "l2_summary": "“It’s really just experience, or at least, my experience. If you only\nwant to time-shift two programs, you don’t need to store a whole\nseason. But I don’t\nwant to point that out just yet. She says, “I just thought about the situation and came up with a\nrecommendation. “Well, I don’t really remember.”\n“That’s how good ideas come to us,” I say. It’s called ‘insight.’ ”", "prev_page": {"page_num": 288, "segment_id": "00288"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 290, "segment_id": "00290"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["just", "only", "ideas", "come", "insight", "want", "need", "thought", "good", "tools"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management|data_science", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["He", "I", "She"], "products": ["giant hard disk", "smaller disks"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Insight and Intuition in Problem Solving", "Price Discrimination Strategy"], "key_concepts": ["insight", "experience-based decision making", "price discrimination"], "problem_statement": "Identifying the root cause 