{"segment_id": "00292", "page_num": 292, "segment": "many kinds of judgments, whether done in a blink or in a month. Of\nspecial concern are judgments about the likelihoods of events, about\none’s own competence relative to others’, and about cause-andeect relationships. In estimating the likelihood of an event, even\nexperienced professionals exhibit predictable biases. For example,\npeople tend to place more weight on vivid examples than on broad\nstatistical evidence.2 My MBA students will each predict that they\nwill get a grade putting them in the top half of the class, even after\nthis information is fed back to them.3 In reasoning about natural\ndata, people tend to see patterns where there is only randomness,\ntend to see causes rather than associations, and tend to ignore\ninformation that conicts with a maintained theory.\n\nTurning back to the participant who brought up Blink, I ask,\n“Would you want the president of the United States to make a\ndecision to go to war in the blink of an eye? Do you think it is\nappropriate for a CEO to decide on a merger without carefully\nthinking through the costs and benets?” These are rhetorical\nquestions, and he nods that he accepts that some issues seem to be\ntoo important and too complex to concede to instant intuition.\n\n“So,” I continue, “in strategy work this quick closure can get us\ninto trouble. Almost by denition, strategy is about very dicult yet\nvery important issues. Because they are important situations, they\nmay deserve more than a quick closure around our rst hunch. You\nknow that. And because you know that, we have a puzzle. Why\nwould experienced executives, like yourselves, go with quick closure in a\nstrategy situation?”\n\nAfter a few moments, a participant says, “There wasn’t enough\n\ntime.”\n\n“Always a problem,” I agree. But I keep scanning the room.\n“It’s a judgment call,” another blurts out. “There is no ‘answer’ to\nthis kind of thing; there is only someone’s judgment about what\nmakes the most sense. There are too many moving parts....”\n\nIt is an acute observation. We are all aware of the basic formal\napproach to making a decision. List the alternatives, gure out the\ncost or value associated with each, and choose the best. But in a\nsituation such as TiVo’s, you cannot perform this kind of clean", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "“So,” I continue, “in strategy work this quick closure can get us\ninto trouble. Why\nwould experienced executives, like yourselves, go with quick closure in a\nstrategy situation?” There are too many moving parts....”", "l2_summary": "many kinds of judgments, whether done in a blink or in a month. “So,” I continue, “in strategy work this quick closure can get us\ninto trouble. Almost by denition, strategy is about very dicult yet\nvery important issues. Because they are important situations, they\nmay deserve more than a quick closure around our rst hunch. Why\nwould experienced executives, like yourselves, go with quick closure in a\nstrategy situation?” There are too many moving parts....”", "prev_page": {"page_num": 291, "segment_id": "00291"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 293, "segment_id": "00293"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["there", "tend", "blink", "than", "important", "strategy", "quick", "closure", "many", "judgments"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["TiVo"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["judgment biases", "strategy decision-making", "quick closure in strategy"], "key_concepts": ["vivid examples bias", "pattern recognition bias", "causal reasoning bias", "first hunch decision making"], "problem_statement": "Experienced executives going with quick closure in complex and important strategic situations", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00293", "page_num": 293, "segment": "“decision” analysis. It is too complex, too ill-structured. Thus, the\nmost experienced executives are actually the quickest to sense that a\nreal strategic situation is impervious to so-called decision analysis.\nThey know that dealing with a strategy situation is, in the end, all\nabout making good judgments. So, they make a judgment call.\n\n“That’s right,” I say. “It is a judgment. In the end, what we\nrecommend will be a best judgment, based on what we know. Still,\nwhy not revisit that judgment and generate alternative views? And,\nwhy not then evaluate them in light of one another? Why the overly\nquick closure on the rst?”\n\nI don’t probe for an answer to this question. I stand up and start\npacing in the front of the room. I tell them that I have observed and\nthought about this for many years and that I have a view about\nwhat happens to us:\n\nFacing a complex situation like this makes most people\nuncomfortable. The more seriously you take it, the more you\nwill see it as a real and dicult challenge that requires a\ncoherent response. And that realization will, in turn, make you\neven more uncomfortable. It is so ill-structured. There are too\nmany variables, so many factors, too many unknowns, no clear\nlist of potential actions and no way to make clear links between\nactions and outcomes. You are not even sure what the problem\nis. Like a swimmer dropped into very choppy waters, it is hard\nto get your bearings. Under pressure to develop a way out of\nthe diculty, that rst idea is a welcome relief. Thank\ngoodness, here is something to hang on to! It feels much better\nto get oriented.\n\nThe problem is that there might be better ideas out there, just\nbeyond the edge of our vision. But we accept early closure\nbecause letting go of a judgment is painful and disconcerting.\nTo search for a new insight, one would have to put aside the\ncomfort of being oriented and once again cast around in choppy\nwaters for a new source of stability. There is the fear of coming\nup empty-handed. Plus, it is unnatural, even painful, to\nquestion our own ideas.", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "It is too complex, too ill-structured. So, they make a judgment call. In the end, what we\nrecommend will be a best judgment, based on what we know.", "l2_summary": "It is too complex, too ill-structured. So, they make a judgment call. In the end, what we\nrecommend will be a best judgment, based on what we know. I tell them that I have observed and\nthought about this for many years and that I have a view about\nwhat happens to us: And that realization will, in turn, make you\neven more uncomfortable. You are not even sure what the problem\nis.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 292, "segment_id": "00292"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 294, "segment_id": "00294"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["judgment", "what", "many", "there", "situation", "make", "will", "have", "more", "even"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "advanced", "companies": [], "people": ["executives"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["strategic decision-making", "judgment calls", "complexity in strategy"], "key_concepts": ["decision analysis", "strategy situations", "judgment calls", "early closure"], "problem_statement": "The difficulty in making strategic decisions due to complexity and the tendency to make quick judgments.", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00294", "page_num": 294, "segment": "Thus, when we do come up with an idea, we tend to spend\nmost of our eort justifying it rather than questioning it. That\nseems to be human nature, even in experienced executives. To\nput it simply, our minds dodge the painful work of questioning\nand letting go of our rst early judgments, and we are not\nconscious of the dodge.\n\nWilling them to understand, I say, “But, you do not have to be a\ncaptive to that unconscious dodge. You can choose how you will\napproach a problem; you can guide your own thinking about it.” I\nwant them to see that this is the heart of the matter. This personal\nskill is more important than any one so-called strategy concept, tool,\nmatrix, or analytical framework. It is the ability to think about your\nown thinking, to make judgments about your own judgments.\n\nSOME TECHNIQUES\n\nTo create strategy in any arena requires a great deal of knowledge\nabout the specics. There is no substitute for on-the-ground\nexperience. This experience accumulates in the form of associations\nbetween situations and “what works” or “what can happen” in those\nsituations. Just as doctors prescribed aspirin for headache and fever\nwithout knowing how it worked, just as the ancient Romans dealt in\nlife insurance without any theory of probability, so you must\nnormally work with patterns and analogies. Of course, in some\ncases, our knowledge is even stronger, and we have theories about\nthe causal structure of the situation---about what causes what.\n\nIn strategy work, knowledge is necessary but not sucient. There\nare many people with deep knowledge or experience who are poor\nat strategy. To guide your own thinking in strategy work, you must\ncultivate three essential skills or habits. First, you must have a\nvariety of tools for ghting your own myopia and for guiding your\nown attention. Second, you must develop the ability to question\nyour own judgment. If your reasoning cannot withstand a vigorous\nattack, your strategy cannot be expected to stand in the face of real", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "It is the ability to think about your\nown thinking, to make judgments about your own judgments. In strategy work, knowledge is necessary but not sucient. To guide your own thinking in strategy work, you must\ncultivate three essential skills or habits.", "l2_summary": "It is the ability to think about your\nown thinking, to make judgments about your own judgments. To create strategy in any arena requires a great deal of knowledge\nabout the specics. In strategy work, knowledge is necessary but not sucient. To guide your own thinking in strategy work, you must\ncultivate three essential skills or habits. First, you must have a\nvariety of tools for ghting your own myopia and for guiding your\nown attention. Second, you must develop the ability to question\nyour own judgment.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 293, "segment_id": "00293"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 295, "segment_id": "00295"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["strategy", "work", "knowledge", "what", "must", "dodge", "judgments", "have", "thinking", "experience"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["they", "you"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["strategy development", 