{"segment_id": "00307", "page_num": 307, "segment": "The concept of cost is tricky. People talk as if products have costs,\nbut that is shorthand easily leading to confusion. Choices, not\nproducts, have costs. The cost of choosing to make one more unit of\na product is sometimes called marginal, or variable, cost. The cost\n(per unit) of choosing to produce at a xed rate for a year is called\naverage cost. The cost per unit of choosing to build a plant and\nproduce at a xed rate is called long-run average cost. The cost of\nlling a rush or special order has no particular name, but it clearly\nexists. There really is no such thing as the single correct “cost” of a\nproduct. It all depends on the decision---on what is being compared\nto what.\n\nThe cost of “deciding” to carry one more telephone call was only\nthat of the electrical power required---essentially zero. The cost of\ndeciding to carry one more call every day for a year was still very\nclose to zero. The cost of deciding to turn on the cable and carry\nthousands of calls every day for a year began to include\nmaintenance and overhead expenses, but not the capital cost of the\nequipment. I began to realize that the “cost” of moving data over all\nof these cables was essentially zero, whether they were fat or\nnarrow. And, with the advent of competition in a formerly\nmonopolized industry, there was nothing keeping prices from falling\nto cost.\n\nThe introductory topic taught in any modern course on business\nstrategy is the connection between industry structure and prot.\nThis topic is usually called the “Five Forces,” following Michael\nPorter’s pioneering analysis of industry structure, published in 1980.\nA quick summary is that a terrible industry looks like this: the\nproduct is an undierentiated commodity; everyone has the same\ncosts and access to the same technology; and buyers are price\nsensitive, knowledgeable, and willing to switch suppliers at a\nmoment’s notice to get a better deal.\n\nIn early 1999 I asked a class of UCLA MBA students to analyze\nGlobal Crossing’s entry into the transatlantic cable business. Step by\nstep the students looked at each aspect of the industry:", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "The concept of cost is tricky. The cost of choosing to make one more unit of\na product is sometimes called marginal, or variable, cost. The cost\n(per unit) of choosing to produce at a xed rate for a year is called\naverage cost.", "l2_summary": "The concept of cost is tricky. The cost of choosing to make one more unit of\na product is sometimes called marginal, or variable, cost. The cost\n(per unit) of choosing to produce at a xed rate for a year is called\naverage cost. The cost per unit of choosing to build a plant and\nproduce at a xed rate is called long-run average cost. There really is no such thing as the single correct “cost” of a\nproduct. The cost of\ndeciding to carry one more call every day for a year was still very\nclose to zero.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 306, "segment_id": "00306"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 308, "segment_id": "00308"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["cost", "industry", "called", "costs", "choosing", "more", "unit", "product", "year", "deciding"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Global Crossing"], "people": ["Michael Porter"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics":