{"segment_id": "00314", "page_num": 314, "segment": "Stearns’s typical leverage was actually more like 50 to 1, but the\ncompany followed a policy of reducing its leverage at the end of\neach month for reporting purposes.) Some of its hedge funds were\nleveraged 85 to 1. Lehman Brothers was about as leveraged as Bear\nStearns. Citigroup, Merrill Lynch, and the rest of Wall Street were\nnot far behind.\n\nThe rst homeowners to walk away from their mortgages in late\n2006 had taken out 90 percent rst mortgages as well as second\n“piggyback” loans to cover the 10 percent down payments. What is\nmore, they had taken out home-equity loans to pay for new\nfurniture and other consumption goods. By 2007, overleveraged\npositions had become epidemic on Wall Street and among a good\nchunk of homeowners.\n\nAs in other credit bubbles in other times and other places, things\nseem ne as long as the value of assets put up as collateral continue\ntheir bubbly rise in value. On the way up, as asset values inate,\ndeal makers, companies, homeowners, and banks all feel that\nborrowings are “secured” by asset values---stocks, homes, and\ncompanies. They feel that there is ground under their feet.\n\nIn the Road Runner cartoons there is the moment when Wile E.\nCoyote mistakenly runs o the top of a cli but continues to hang in\nthe air, his feet churning. Not until he looks down and sees that\nthere is nothing under his feet does he begin to fall. In credit\nbubbles, that moment comes when asset prices rst begin to decline.\nIt takes only a gentle deation of the asset bubble to trigger the\ncollapse. As asset prices begin to drift downward, investors who\nhave recently bought inated assets using high leverage suddenly\nrealize there is no ground under their feet. The more nimble rush to\nsell before their equity is wiped out. And those sales, in turn, drive\ndown prices faster. This new downward lurch in prices panics still\nmore overleveraged owners and they, too, rush to sell. This process\nis called “unwinding” or “deleveraging.” As large numbers of people\ntry to unwind at the same time, the selling pressure makes asset prices\nfall even more sharply. Bankers, suddenly regaining their sanity, also\nstart deleveraging, which reduces the amount of credit available in\nthe economy. The slowing economy causes even more defaults and", "source_file": "GOOD-STRATEGY-BAD-STRATEGY.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "1", "chapter_title": ", “Good Strategy Is Unexpected,” and chapter 2,", "section_num": "2.0", "section_title": "businesses. The term “Web 2.0” purportedly referred to a", "l1_summary": "What is\nmore, they had taken out home-equity loans to pay for new\nfurniture and other consumption goods. They feel that there is ground under their feet. In credit\nbubbles, that moment comes when asset prices rst begin to decline.", "l2_summary": "The rst homeowners to walk away from their mortgages in late\n2006 had taken out 90 percent rst mortgages as well as second\n“piggyback” loans to cover the 10 percent down payments. What is\nmore, they had taken out home-equity loans to pay for new\nfurniture and other consumption goods. They feel that there is ground under their feet. Not until he looks down and sees that\nthere is nothing under his feet does he begin to fall. In credit\nbubbles, that moment comes when asset prices rst begin to decline. The more nimble rush to\nsell before their equity is wiped out.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 313, "segment_id": "00313"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 315, "segment_id": "00315"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["more", "asset", "prices", "other", "there", "feet", "leverage", "homeowners", "down", "credit"], "content_type": "reference", "domain": "finance|economics", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Bear Stearns", "Lehman Brothers", "Citigroup", "Merrill Lynch"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Leverage in Financial Institutions", "Subprime Mortgage Crisis"], "key_concepts": ["leverage", "asset bubble", "unwinding", "deleveraging"], "problem_statement": "The over-leveraged positions and subprime mortgages leading to financial instability.", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
